1
00:01:04,569 --> 00:01:09,569
<i>My dear Frodo:

2
00:01:12,911 --> 00:01:14,578
<i>You asked me once...

3
00:01:14,579 --> 00:01:19,458
<i>...if I had told you everything
there was to know about my adventures.

4
00:01:19,459 --> 00:01:20,751
<i>And while I can honestly...

5
00:01:20,752 --> 00:01:22,044
<i>...say I have told you...

6
00:01:22,045 --> 00:01:24,421
<i>...the truth...

7
00:01:24,422 --> 00:01:29,422
<i>...I may not have told you all of it.

8
00:01:34,724 --> 00:01:38,268
<i>I am old now, Frodo.

9
00:01:38,269 --> 00:01:43,269
<i>I'm not the same Hobbit I once was.

10
00:01:44,317 --> 00:01:46,026
<i>I think...

11
00:01:46,027 --> 00:01:49,029
<i>...it is time for you to know...

12
00:01:49,030 --> 00:01:53,200
<i>...what really happened.

13
00:01:53,201 --> 00:01:54,952
<i>It began...

14
00:01:54,953 --> 00:01:57,746
<i>...long ago...

15
00:01:57,747 --> 00:02:01,125
<i>...in a land far away to the east...

16
00:02:01,126 --> 00:02:06,126
<i>...the like of which you will not find
in the world today.

17
00:02:16,099 --> 00:02:18,809
<i>There was the city of Dale.

18
00:02:18,810 --> 00:02:20,144
<i>Its markets known...

19
00:02:20,145 --> 00:02:21,437
<i>...far and wide.

20
00:02:21,438 --> 00:02:25,607
<i>Full of the bounties of vine and vale.

21
00:02:25,608 --> 00:02:30,608
<i>Peaceful and prosperous.

22
00:02:30,780 --> 00:02:33,282
<i>For this city lay before the doors...

23
00:02:33,283 --> 00:02:37,202
<i>...of the greatest kingdom in Middle-earth:

24
00:02:37,203 --> 00:02:39,580
<i>Erebor.

25
00:02:39,581 --> 00:02:41,874
<i>Stronghold of Thror...

26
00:02:41,875 --> 00:02:44,877
<i>...King Under the Mountain. Mightiest...

27
00:02:44,878 --> 00:02:47,838
<i>...of the Dwarf Lords.

28
00:02:47,839 --> 00:02:50,757
<i>Thror ruled with utter surety...

29
00:02:50,758 --> 00:02:53,385
<i>...never doubting his house would endure...

30
00:02:53,386 --> 00:02:54,845
<i>...for his line lay secure...

31
00:02:54,846 --> 00:02:57,598
<i>...in the lives of his son...

32
00:02:57,599 --> 00:03:00,601
<i>...and grandson.

33
00:03:00,602 --> 00:03:04,062
<i>Ah, Frodo. Erebor.

34
00:03:04,063 --> 00:03:06,523
<i>Built deep within the mountain itself...

35
00:03:06,524 --> 00:03:10,360
<i>...the beauty of this fortress city was legend.

36
00:03:10,361 --> 00:03:13,113
<i>Its wealth lay in the earth...

37
00:03:13,114 --> 00:03:15,032
<i>...in precious gems hewn...

38
00:03:15,033 --> 00:03:18,368
<i>...from rock and in great seams of gold...

39
00:03:18,369 --> 00:03:23,369
<i>...running like rivers through stone.

40
00:03:24,083 --> 00:03:25,918
<i>The skill of the Dwarves...

41
00:03:25,919 --> 00:03:28,921
<i>...was unequaled, fashioning objects...

42
00:03:28,922 --> 00:03:31,757
<i>...of great beauty...

43
00:03:31,758 --> 00:03:36,053
<i>...out of diamond, emerald,
ruby and sapphire.

44
00:03:36,054 --> 00:03:37,846
<i>Ever they delved deeper...

45
00:03:37,847 --> 00:03:40,599
<i>...down into the dark.

46
00:03:40,600 --> 00:03:45,600
<i>And that is where they found it.

47
00:03:49,484 --> 00:03:53,445
<i>The Heart of the Mountain.

48
00:03:53,446 --> 00:03:56,240
<i>The Arkenstone.

49
00:03:56,241 --> 00:03:59,284
<i>Thror named it "The King's Jewel".

50
00:03:59,285 --> 00:04:02,454
<i>He took it as a sign,
a sign that his right to rule...

51
00:04:02,455 --> 00:04:04,331
<i>...was divine.

52
00:04:04,332 --> 00:04:05,749
<i>All would pay...

53
00:04:05,750 --> 00:04:07,042
<i>...homage to him.

54
00:04:07,043 --> 00:04:08,293
Even the great...

55
00:04:08,294 --> 00:04:13,294
<i>...Elven King, Thranduil.

56
00:04:16,219 --> 00:04:20,639
<i>As the great wealth of the Dwarves grew...

57
00:04:20,640 --> 00:04:25,640
<i>...their store of good will ran thin.

58
00:04:25,937 --> 00:04:30,937
<i>No one knows exactly what began the rift.

59
00:04:31,651 --> 00:04:32,651
<i>The Elves say...

60
00:04:32,652 --> 00:04:35,237
<i>...the Dwarves stole their treasure.

61
00:04:35,238 --> 00:04:36,989
<i>The Dwarves tell another tale.

62
00:04:36,990 --> 00:04:41,660
<i>They say the Elf King
refused to give them their rightful pay.

63
00:04:41,661 --> 00:04:44,121
<i>It is sad, Frodo, how old alliances...

64
00:04:44,122 --> 00:04:45,455
<i>...can be broken.

65
00:04:45,456 --> 00:04:48,875
<i>How friendships between peoples
can be lost.

66
00:04:48,876 --> 00:04:51,712
And for what?

67
00:04:59,762 --> 00:05:03,557
<i>Slowly the days turned sour...

68
00:05:03,558 --> 00:05:08,558
<i>...and the watchful nights closed in.

69
00:05:15,153 --> 00:05:17,696
<i>Thror's love of gold...

70
00:05:17,697 --> 00:05:21,283
<i>...had grown too fierce.

71
00:05:21,284 --> 00:05:26,079
<i>A sickness had begun to grow within him.

72
00:05:26,080 --> 00:05:31,080
<i>It was a sickness of the mind.

73
00:05:31,461 --> 00:05:35,005
<i>And where sickness thrives...

74
00:05:35,006 --> 00:05:40,006
<i>...bad things will follow.

75
00:05:46,309 --> 00:05:48,894
<i>The first they heard
was a noise...

76
00:05:48,895 --> 00:05:50,771
<i>...like a hurricane coming down...

77
00:05:50,772 --> 00:05:51,980
<i>...from the North.

78
00:05:51,981 --> 00:05:54,775
<i>The pines on the mountain
creaked and cracked...

79
00:05:54,776 --> 00:05:57,361
<i>...in the hot, dry wind.

80
00:06:01,324 --> 00:06:04,743
Balin, sound the alarm.

81
00:06:06,579 --> 00:06:08,664
Call out the guard. Do it now!

82
00:06:08,665 --> 00:06:10,123
What is it?

83
00:06:10,124 --> 00:06:12,292
Dragon.

84
00:06:12,293 --> 00:06:16,630
Dragon!

85
00:06:16,631 --> 00:06:17,589
<i>He was...

86
00:06:17,590 --> 00:06:22,590
<i>...a firedrake from the North.

87
00:06:26,891 --> 00:06:28,767
<i>Smaug...

88
00:06:28,768 --> 00:06:33,768
<i>...had come.

89
00:07:02,760 --> 00:07:04,594
<i>Such wanton death...

90
00:07:04,595 --> 00:07:08,056
<i>...was dealt that day.

91
00:07:08,057 --> 00:07:09,766
<i>For this city of Men was nothing...

92
00:07:09,767 --> 00:07:11,768
<i>...to Smaug.

93
00:07:11,769 --> 00:07:12,811
<i>His eye...

94
00:07:12,812 --> 00:07:17,812
<i>...was set on another prize.

95
00:07:20,361 --> 00:07:21,570
<i>For dragons...

96
00:07:21,571 --> 00:07:23,488
<i>...covet gold...

97
00:07:23,489 --> 00:07:24,573
<i>...with a dark and...

98
00:07:24,574 --> 00:07:29,574
<i>...fierce desire.

99
00:07:32,999 --> 00:07:37,999
<font color=#FF8000>Therk√¢!</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(Steady!)</font>

100
00:07:54,187 --> 00:07:58,940
Aah!

101
00:07:58,941 --> 00:08:03,941
No!

102
00:08:05,948 --> 00:08:08,533
Come on.

103
00:08:08,534 --> 00:08:13,534
<i>Erebor was lost.

104
00:08:15,917 --> 00:08:16,833
<i>For a dragon...

105
00:08:16,834 --> 00:08:19,419
<i>...will guard his plunder...

106
00:08:19,420 --> 00:08:24,420
<i>...as long as he lives.

107
00:08:30,306 --> 00:08:32,307
Run for your lives!

108
00:08:32,308 --> 00:08:37,308
Ah! Help us!

109
00:08:47,406 --> 00:08:50,992
<i>Thranduil would not risk
the lives of his kin against...

110
00:08:50,993 --> 00:08:53,161
<i>...the wrath of the dragon.

111
00:08:53,162 --> 00:08:55,038
<i>No help came from the Elves...

112
00:08:55,039 --> 00:09:00,039
<i>...that day, nor any day since.

113
00:09:00,920 --> 00:09:03,380
<i>Robbed of their homeland...

114
00:09:03,381 --> 00:09:06,925
<i>...the Dwarves of Erebor
wandered the wilderness...

115
00:09:06,926 --> 00:09:11,926
<i>...a once mighty people brought low.

116
00:09:12,515 --> 00:09:16,184
<i>The young Dwarf prince took work
where he could find it...

117
00:09:16,185 --> 00:09:18,687
<i>...laboring in the villages of Men.

118
00:09:18,688 --> 00:09:21,398
<i>But always he remembered...

119
00:09:21,399 --> 00:09:24,025
<i>...the mountain smoke beneath the moon...

120
00:09:24,026 --> 00:09:27,445
<i>...the trees like torches blazing bright.

121
00:09:27,446 --> 00:09:29,197
<i>For he had seen dragon fire...

122
00:09:29,198 --> 00:09:30,949
...in the sky...

123
00:09:30,950 --> 00:09:35,829
<i>...and a city turned to ash.

124
00:09:35,830 --> 00:09:37,831
<i>And he never forgave...

125
00:09:37,832 --> 00:09:40,417
<i>...and he never forgot.

126
00:09:43,087 --> 00:09:45,589
<i>Far away, in another corner of the world...

127
00:09:45,590 --> 00:09:46,506
<i>...dragons were...

128
00:09:46,507 --> 00:09:47,507
...only make-believe.

129
00:09:47,508 --> 00:09:48,550
Up they go!

130
00:09:48,551 --> 00:09:49,551
<i>A party trick...

131
00:09:49,552 --> 00:09:50,802
<i>...conjured by Wizards...

132
00:09:50,803 --> 00:09:52,470
<i>...on Midsummer's Eve.

133
00:09:52,471 --> 00:09:53,388
<i>No more frightening...

134
00:09:53,389 --> 00:09:54,681
<i>...than fairy dust.

135
00:09:57,143 --> 00:09:58,184
Bilbo!

136
00:09:58,185 --> 00:10:00,645
<i>And that, my dear Frodo...

137
00:10:00,646 --> 00:10:01,605
<i>...is where I come in.

138
00:10:01,606 --> 00:10:05,108
Bilbo! Bilbo.

139
00:10:05,109 --> 00:10:08,987
<i>It was the beginning
of an unlikely friendship...

140
00:10:08,988 --> 00:10:11,865
<i>...that has lasted all my life.

141
00:10:14,702 --> 00:10:19,581
<i>But it is not the start of my story.
For me, it began...

142
00:10:19,582 --> 00:10:23,543
<i>Well, it began as you might expect.

143
00:10:23,544 --> 00:10:26,922
<i>In a hole in the ground, there lived...

144
00:10:26,923 --> 00:10:30,175
<i>...a Hobbit.

145
00:10:30,176 --> 00:10:35,176
<i>Not a nasty, dirty, wet hole
full of worms and oozy smells.

146
00:10:35,932 --> 00:10:38,266
<i>This was a Hobbit hole.

147
00:10:38,267 --> 00:10:43,267
<i>And that means good food, a warm hearth...

148
00:10:43,981 --> 00:10:48,981
<i>...and all the comforts of home.

149
00:11:21,185 --> 00:11:23,895
Thank you.

150
00:11:23,896 --> 00:11:25,522
What's this?

151
00:11:25,523 --> 00:11:26,898
That is private.

152
00:11:26,899 --> 00:11:29,901
Keep your sticky paws off.

153
00:11:29,902 --> 00:11:32,195
It's not ready yet.

154
00:11:32,196 --> 00:11:33,905
Not ready for what?

155
00:11:33,906 --> 00:11:38,906
Reading.

156
00:11:39,412 --> 00:11:41,621
What on earth are these?

157
00:11:41,622 --> 00:11:43,665
Replies to the party invitations.

158
00:11:43,666 --> 00:11:48,211
Ah. Good gracious. Is it today?

159
00:11:48,212 --> 00:11:49,796
They all say they're coming.

160
00:11:49,797 --> 00:11:53,800
Except for the Sackville-Bagginses,
who are demanding you ask them in person.

161
00:11:53,801 --> 00:11:56,469
Are they, indeed? Over my...

162
00:11:56,470 --> 00:11:58,513
- ...dead body.
- They'd probably find that...

163
00:11:58,514 --> 00:11:59,597
...quite agreeable.

164
00:11:59,598 --> 00:12:01,975
They seem to think you have tunnels
overflowing with gold.

165
00:12:01,976 --> 00:12:06,354
It was one small chest, hardly overflowing.

166
00:12:06,355 --> 00:12:09,065
And it still smells of Troll.

167
00:12:09,066 --> 00:12:10,650
What on earth are you doing?

168
00:12:13,654 --> 00:12:16,573
Taking precautions. You know...

169
00:12:16,574 --> 00:12:19,200
...I caught her making off
with the silverware once.

170
00:12:19,201 --> 00:12:23,163
- Who?
- Lobelia Sackville-Baggins.

171
00:12:23,164 --> 00:12:26,791
She had all my spoons
stuffed in her pocket. Ha!

172
00:12:26,792 --> 00:12:28,168
Dreadful woman.

173
00:12:28,169 --> 00:12:32,547
Make sure you keep an eye on her
after I'm...

174
00:12:32,548 --> 00:12:35,300
When I'm... When I'm...

175
00:12:35,301 --> 00:12:40,301
When you're what?

176
00:12:41,223 --> 00:12:46,223
It's nothing. Nothing.

177
00:12:49,190 --> 00:12:52,525
You know, some people are beginning
to wonder about you, Uncle.

178
00:12:52,526 --> 00:12:55,403
- Huh?
- They think you're becoming odd.

179
00:12:55,404 --> 00:12:58,073
Odd? Oh. Hm.

180
00:12:58,074 --> 00:12:59,574
Unsociable.

181
00:12:59,575 --> 00:13:02,660
Unsociable, me? Nonsense.

182
00:13:02,661 --> 00:13:04,120
Be a good lad and put that...

183
00:13:04,121 --> 00:13:09,121
...on the gate.

184
00:13:14,757 --> 00:13:16,424
Do you think he'll come?

185
00:13:16,425 --> 00:13:17,759
Who?

186
00:13:17,760 --> 00:13:19,010
Gandalf.

187
00:13:19,011 --> 00:13:23,223
Oh-ho. He wouldn't miss a chance
to let off his Whizpoppers. He'll give us...

188
00:13:23,224 --> 00:13:24,891
...quite a show, you'll see.

189
00:13:24,892 --> 00:13:27,227
- Right, then. I'm off.
- Off to where?

190
00:13:27,228 --> 00:13:29,562
East-farthing Woods.
I'm going to surprise him.

191
00:13:29,563 --> 00:13:34,563
Well, go on, then. You don't want to be late.

192
00:13:37,446 --> 00:13:42,117
<i>He doesn't approve of being late.
Not that I...

193
00:13:42,118 --> 00:13:43,743
<i>...ever was.

194
00:13:43,744 --> 00:13:47,372
<i>In those days, I was always on time.

195
00:13:47,373 --> 00:13:51,459
<i>I was entirely respectable.

196
00:13:51,460 --> 00:13:55,672
<i>And nothing unexpected...

197
00:13:55,673 --> 00:14:00,673
<i>...ever happened.

198
00:14:16,522 --> 00:14:20,359


199
00:14:21,615 --> 00:14:24,367
- Good morning.
- What do you mean?

200
00:14:24,368 --> 00:14:28,288
Do you wish me a good morning
or do you mean that it is a good morning...

201
00:14:28,289 --> 00:14:30,665
...whether I want it or not'?

202
00:14:30,666 --> 00:14:35,420
Or perhaps you mean to say that you feel good
on this particular morning?

203
00:14:35,421 --> 00:14:40,421
Or are you simply stating
that this is a morning to be good on? Hm?

204
00:14:40,718 --> 00:14:44,012
All of them at once, I suppose.

205
00:14:44,013 --> 00:14:49,013
Hmm.

206
00:14:49,518 --> 00:14:50,852
Can I help you?

207
00:14:50,853 --> 00:14:54,772
That remains to be seen.

208
00:14:54,773 --> 00:14:59,773
I'm looking for someone
to share in an adventure.

209
00:15:02,114 --> 00:15:05,533
An adventure?

210
00:15:05,534 --> 00:15:10,534
No, I don't imagine anyone west of Bree
would have much interest in adventures.

211
00:15:11,415 --> 00:15:16,252
Nasty, disturbing, uncomfortable things.

212
00:15:16,253 --> 00:15:18,838
Make you late for dinner. Heh, heh.

213
00:15:18,839 --> 00:15:19,839
Mm.

214
00:15:19,840 --> 00:15:21,925
Huh.

215
00:15:21,926 --> 00:15:24,552
<i>Hmm.

216
00:15:24,553 --> 00:15:26,888
Oh. Ah.

217
00:15:26,889 --> 00:15:28,223
Good morning.

218
00:15:28,224 --> 00:15:31,309
To think that I should have lived
to be "good morninged"...

219
00:15:31,310 --> 00:15:36,310
...by Belladonna Took's son
as if I were selling buttons at the door.

220
00:15:36,482 --> 00:15:38,608
Beg your pardon?

221
00:15:38,609 --> 00:15:40,568
You've changed,
and not entirely for the better...

222
00:15:40,569 --> 00:15:41,945
...Bilbo Baggins.

223
00:15:41,946 --> 00:15:43,363
I'm sorry, do I know you?

224
00:15:43,364 --> 00:15:46,699
Well, you know my name,
although you don't remember I belong to it.

225
00:15:46,700 --> 00:15:48,368
I'm Gandalf.

226
00:15:48,369 --> 00:15:52,538
And Gandalf means...

227
00:15:52,539 --> 00:15:54,290
...me.

228
00:15:54,291 --> 00:15:56,542
Gandalf?
Not Gandalf the wandering Wizard...

229
00:15:56,543 --> 00:15:58,044
...who made such excellent...

230
00:15:58,045 --> 00:16:03,007
...fireworks? Old Took used to have them
on Midsummer's Eve. Heh, heh. Ahem.

231
00:16:03,008 --> 00:16:05,885
No idea you were still in business.

232
00:16:05,886 --> 00:16:07,595
And where else should I be?

233
00:16:07,596 --> 00:16:12,267
Where else...? Ahem.

234
00:16:12,268 --> 00:16:16,312
Well, I'm pleased to find you remember
something about me...

235
00:16:16,313 --> 00:16:19,857
...even if it's only my fireworks.

236
00:16:19,858 --> 00:16:22,527
Yes. Well, that's decided.

237
00:16:22,528 --> 00:16:25,905
It'll be very good for you...

238
00:16:25,906 --> 00:16:27,740
...and most amusing for me.

239
00:16:27,741 --> 00:16:29,575
I shall inform the others.

240
00:16:29,576 --> 00:16:33,037
Inform the who? What? No. No. No... Wait.

241
00:16:33,038 --> 00:16:34,414
We do not want...

242
00:16:34,415 --> 00:16:38,793
...any adventures here,
thank you. Not today. Not...

243
00:16:38,794 --> 00:16:43,794
I suggest you try Over the Hill
or Across the Water.

244
00:16:45,634 --> 00:16:50,634
Good morning.

245
00:17:36,143 --> 00:17:41,143
Morning!

246
00:17:51,116 --> 00:17:53,659
Twelve. There we go. Have a very good day.

247
00:18:14,473 --> 00:18:18,101
Chum.

248
00:18:18,102 --> 00:18:20,812
Hello, Mr. Bilbo. Here.

249
00:18:20,813 --> 00:18:24,607
Have a feel of me tubers.
Nice and firm, they are.

250
00:18:24,608 --> 00:18:27,402
- Just come in from West Farthing.
- Very impressive, Mr. Worrywort.

251
00:18:27,403 --> 00:18:31,364
Now, I don't suppose you've seen
a Wizard lurking around these parts?

252
00:18:31,365 --> 00:18:32,907
A tall fellow.

253
00:18:32,908 --> 00:18:34,158
Long, gray beard.

254
00:18:34,159 --> 00:18:36,577
Pointy hat.

255
00:18:36,578 --> 00:18:41,578
Can't say I have.

256
00:19:26,253 --> 00:19:29,881
Dwalin, at your service.

257
00:19:29,882 --> 00:19:32,800
Hm. Uh...

258
00:19:32,801 --> 00:19:37,013
Bilbo Baggins, at yours.

259
00:19:37,014 --> 00:19:38,139
Do we...

260
00:19:38,140 --> 00:19:39,891
...know each other?

261
00:19:39,892 --> 00:19:42,059
No.

262
00:19:42,060 --> 00:19:43,853
Which way, laddie?

263
00:19:43,854 --> 00:19:45,354
Is it down here?

264
00:19:45,355 --> 00:19:46,439
Is what...

265
00:19:46,440 --> 00:19:47,899
...down where?

266
00:19:47,900 --> 00:19:49,609
<i>Supper.

267
00:19:49,610 --> 00:19:52,487
He said there'd be food and lots of it.

268
00:19:52,488 --> 00:19:57,488
He... He said? Who said?

269
00:19:57,826 --> 00:20:02,826
Mmm.

270
00:20:03,707 --> 00:20:06,292
Mmm.

271
00:20:06,293 --> 00:20:09,754
Very good, this. Any more?

272
00:20:09,755 --> 00:20:12,173
What? Oh, yes, yes.

273
00:20:12,174 --> 00:20:17,174
Ah.

274
00:20:19,181 --> 00:20:23,643
Help yourself.

275
00:20:23,644 --> 00:20:28,644
Hmm. It's just that, um,
I wasn't expecting company.

276
00:20:32,361 --> 00:20:37,361
That'll be the door.

277
00:20:38,492 --> 00:20:39,492
Balin...

278
00:20:39,493 --> 00:20:42,370
...at your service.

279
00:20:42,371 --> 00:20:43,412
Good evening.

280
00:20:43,413 --> 00:20:45,831
Yes. Yes, it is.

281
00:20:45,832 --> 00:20:48,501
- Though I think it might rain later.
- Hm?

282
00:20:48,502 --> 00:20:50,294
Am I late?

283
00:20:50,295 --> 00:20:52,630
Late for what?

284
00:20:52,631 --> 00:20:53,589
Oh!

285
00:20:53,590 --> 00:20:55,466
Ha, ha!

286
00:20:55,467 --> 00:20:57,385
Evening, brother.

287
00:20:58,512 --> 00:21:00,846
By my beard...

288
00:21:00,847 --> 00:21:04,016
...you're shorter and wider than last we met.

289
00:21:04,017 --> 00:21:06,227
Wider, not shorter.

290
00:21:06,228 --> 00:21:09,313
Sharp enough for both of us.

291
00:21:17,739 --> 00:21:20,783
Uh, excuse me? Sorry, I hate to interrupt.

292
00:21:20,784 --> 00:21:25,079
But the thing is, I'm not entirely sure
you're in the right house.

293
00:21:25,080 --> 00:21:27,290
- Have you eaten?
- It's not that I don't like...

294
00:21:27,291 --> 00:21:29,125
...visitors. I like visitors...

295
00:21:29,126 --> 00:21:31,419
...as much as the next Hobbit.

296
00:21:31,420 --> 00:21:35,172
But I do like to know them
before they come visiting.

297
00:21:35,173 --> 00:21:36,674
- What is this?
- I don't know.

298
00:21:36,675 --> 00:21:39,802
- I think it's cheese. Gone blue.
- It's riddled with mold.

299
00:21:39,803 --> 00:21:44,803
The thing is, I don't know either of you.
Not in the slightest. I don't mean...

300
00:21:45,392 --> 00:21:47,643
...to be blunt, but I had to speak my mind.

301
00:21:47,644 --> 00:21:50,104
- I'm sorry.
- You think...?

302
00:21:52,482 --> 00:21:54,025
Apology accepted.

303
00:21:54,026 --> 00:21:55,693
- Ah.
- Now, fill it up, brother...

304
00:21:55,694 --> 00:21:56,611
...don't stint.

305
00:21:57,779 --> 00:22:01,574
- You wanna get stuck in?
- I could eat again if you insist, brother.

306
00:22:02,993 --> 00:22:05,036
- Fili.
- And Kili.

307
00:22:05,037 --> 00:22:07,038
At your service.

308
00:22:07,039 --> 00:22:08,623
You must be Mr. Boggins.

309
00:22:08,624 --> 00:22:10,958
Nope! You can't come in.
You've come to the wrong house.

310
00:22:10,959 --> 00:22:12,084
What?

311
00:22:12,085 --> 00:22:14,879
- Has it been canceled?
- No one told us.

312
00:22:14,880 --> 00:22:16,464
No, nothing's been canceled.

313
00:22:16,465 --> 00:22:21,465
That's a relief.

314
00:22:21,595 --> 00:22:23,137
Careful with these.

315
00:22:23,138 --> 00:22:25,556
I just had them sharpened.

316
00:22:25,557 --> 00:22:27,475
- It's nice, this place.
- Yeah.

317
00:22:27,476 --> 00:22:30,936
- Did you do it yourself?
- What? No, it's been in the family for years.

318
00:22:30,937 --> 00:22:33,981
That's my mother's glory box.
Can you please not do that?

319
00:22:33,982 --> 00:22:36,776
Fili, Kili. Come on, give us a hand.

320
00:22:36,777 --> 00:22:39,904
Mr. Dwalin. Ha, ha.

321
00:22:39,905 --> 00:22:43,115
Shove this in the hallway.
Otherwise we'll never get everyone in.

322
00:22:43,116 --> 00:22:46,160
- "Everyone"? How many more are there?
- Where do you want this?

323
00:22:46,161 --> 00:22:48,245
- Oh, no.
- It's really heavy.

324
00:22:48,246 --> 00:22:51,040
No. No. There's nobody home!

325
00:22:51,041 --> 00:22:53,959
Go away and bother somebody else.

326
00:22:53,960 --> 00:22:57,338
There's far too many Dwarves
in my dining room as it is.

327
00:22:57,339 --> 00:23:01,467
If this is some clot-head's idea of a joke...

328
00:23:01,468 --> 00:23:04,136
...I can only say it is in very...

329
00:23:04,137 --> 00:23:05,846
...poor taste.

330
00:23:07,224 --> 00:23:08,182
Get off...

331
00:23:08,183 --> 00:23:09,558
...you big lump!

332
00:23:14,940 --> 00:23:16,565
Gandalf.

333
00:23:20,612 --> 00:23:22,822
Excuse me, that's my chicken. Um...

334
00:23:22,823 --> 00:23:26,283
If-- If you don't...
That's my wine. Excuse me!

335
00:23:26,284 --> 00:23:29,620
<font color=#FF8000>Khuzd Belkul!</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(A mighty Dwarf!)</font>

336
00:23:29,621 --> 00:23:32,665
He's got an injury.

337
00:23:32,666 --> 00:23:34,125
You mean the ax in his head?

338
00:23:34,126 --> 00:23:37,169
Dead? No, only between his ears.

339
00:23:37,170 --> 00:23:41,674
His legs work fine.

340
00:23:41,675 --> 00:23:43,050
Put those back.

341
00:23:43,051 --> 00:23:44,135
Put that back.

342
00:23:44,136 --> 00:23:45,428
Put that back.

343
00:23:45,429 --> 00:23:46,345
Not the jam.

344
00:23:46,346 --> 00:23:47,513
Excuse me. Excuse me.

345
00:23:47,514 --> 00:23:50,599
It's a tad excessive, isn't it?
Have you got a cheese knife?

346
00:23:50,600 --> 00:23:53,644
- "Cheese knife"? He eats it by the block.
- Ugh.

347
00:23:53,645 --> 00:23:57,231
No, that's Grandpa Mungo's chair...
No, so is that. Take it back, please.

348
00:23:57,232 --> 00:24:01,610
- I cannot hear what you're saying.
- It's an antique. Not for sitting on.

349
00:24:01,611 --> 00:24:06,611
That is a book, not a coaster.
And put that map down.

350
00:24:07,159 --> 00:24:09,368
- Excuse me, Mr. Gandalf?
- Yes?

351
00:24:09,369 --> 00:24:12,204
May I tempt you with a cup of chamomile?

352
00:24:12,205 --> 00:24:17,205
Oh, no, thank you, Dori.
A little red wine for me, I think.

353
00:24:19,463 --> 00:24:24,383
- Whoop! Mind out.
- Yes. Ah.

354
00:24:24,384 --> 00:24:27,428
Uh, Fili, Kili. Uh...

355
00:24:27,429 --> 00:24:29,722
Oin, Gloin.

356
00:24:29,723 --> 00:24:32,892
Dwalin, Balin, Bifur, Bofur, Bombur...

357
00:24:32,893 --> 00:24:35,770
- ...Dori, Nori. Ori!
- No. Not my prizewinners, thank you.

358
00:24:35,771 --> 00:24:38,022
No, thank you.

359
00:24:36,500 --> 00:24:40,483
<font color=#FF8000>Lu zayara, maima mut karima.</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(Our great leader, he is not here.)</font>

360
00:24:40,484 --> 00:24:43,152
Yes, you're quite right, Bifur.

361
00:24:43,153 --> 00:24:45,654
We appear to be one Dwarf short.

362
00:24:45,655 --> 00:24:50,655
He is late, is all. He traveled north
to a meeting of our kin. He will come.

363
00:24:51,244 --> 00:24:55,164
Mr. Gandalf? A little glass of red wine,
as requested.

364
00:24:55,165 --> 00:24:57,374
It's got a fruity bouquet.

365
00:24:57,375 --> 00:24:59,877
Oh. Cheers.

366
00:24:59,878 --> 00:25:04,381
Bombur's on his second leg of lamb already.

367
00:25:04,382 --> 00:25:05,633
Hmm.

368
00:25:06,843 --> 00:25:09,512
No chance. Not from that distance.

369
00:25:09,513 --> 00:25:11,639
Wanna bet? Bombur...

370
00:25:11,640 --> 00:25:13,140
...catch!

371
00:25:15,894 --> 00:25:17,853
I'll help you with that.

372
00:25:24,569 --> 00:25:25,611
Oh, you great...

373
00:25:25,612 --> 00:25:26,904
...galumphing git!

374
00:25:26,905 --> 00:25:28,197
Who wants an ale? There you go.

375
00:25:28,198 --> 00:25:30,115
Over here, brother.

376
00:25:30,116 --> 00:25:31,367
I said have another...

377
00:25:31,368 --> 00:25:33,577
...drink. Here you go.

378
00:25:38,458 --> 00:25:40,042
Ale on the count of three!

379
00:25:40,043 --> 00:25:40,960
One...

380
00:25:40,961 --> 00:25:45,961
- ...two...
- Up!

381
00:25:53,849 --> 00:25:55,516
I knew you had it in you!

382
00:25:55,517 --> 00:25:58,310
Excuse me, that is a doily, not a dishcloth.

383
00:25:58,311 --> 00:25:59,603
But it's full of holes.

384
00:25:59,604 --> 00:26:02,022
It's supposed to look like that. It's crochet.

385
00:26:02,023 --> 00:26:05,192
And a wonderful game it is too,
if you've got the balls for it.

386
00:26:05,193 --> 00:26:07,278
Bebother and confusticate these Dwarves!

387
00:26:07,279 --> 00:26:10,197
My dear Bilbo, what on earth is the matter?

388
00:26:10,198 --> 00:26:13,200
What's the matter?
I'm surrounded by Dwarves.

389
00:26:13,201 --> 00:26:14,952
What are they doing here?

390
00:26:14,953 --> 00:26:18,873
Oh, they're quite a merry gathering
once you get used to them.

391
00:26:18,874 --> 00:26:21,000
I don't want to get used to them.

392
00:26:21,001 --> 00:26:24,336
Look at the state of my kitchen.
There's mud trod into the carpet.

393
00:26:24,337 --> 00:26:25,921
They've pillaged the pantry.

394
00:26:25,922 --> 00:26:28,507
I won't tell you what they've done
in the bathroom.

395
00:26:28,508 --> 00:26:32,553
They've destroyed the plumbing. I don't
understand what they're doing in my house!

396
00:26:32,554 --> 00:26:37,554
Excuse me. I'm sorry to interrupt,
but what should I do with my plate?

397
00:26:37,934 --> 00:26:42,934
Here you go, Ori. Give it to me.

398
00:26:44,900 --> 00:26:45,816
Take that back.

399
00:26:45,817 --> 00:26:46,942
Excuse me.

400
00:26:46,943 --> 00:26:48,235
That's my mother's...

401
00:26:48,236 --> 00:26:49,987
...West Farthing pottery. It's over...

402
00:26:49,988 --> 00:26:54,617
...100 years old!

403
00:26:54,618 --> 00:26:55,534
And can you...

404
00:26:55,535 --> 00:26:56,535
...not do that?

405
00:26:56,536 --> 00:26:57,453
You'll blunt them.

406
00:26:57,454 --> 00:26:59,997
Ooh. Do you hear that, lads?

407
00:26:59,998 --> 00:27:01,040
He says...

408
00:27:01,041 --> 00:27:02,958
...we'll blunt the knives.

409
00:27:02,959 --> 00:27:05,044
<i>Blunt the knives, bend the forks

410
00:27:05,045 --> 00:27:07,713
<i>Smash the bottles and burn the corks

411
00:27:07,714 --> 00:27:10,674
<i>Chip the glasses and crack the plates

412
00:27:10,675 --> 00:27:12,259
<i>That's what Bilbo Baggins

413
00:27:12,260 --> 00:27:13,177
<i>Hates

414
00:27:13,178 --> 00:27:14,803
<i>Cut the cloth, tread on the fat

415
00:27:14,804 --> 00:27:16,847
<i>Leave the bones on the bedroom mat

416
00:27:16,848 --> 00:27:20,517
<i>Pour the milk on the pantry floor

417
00:27:20,518 --> 00:27:21,852
<i>Splash the wine

418
00:27:21,853 --> 00:27:22,770
<i>On every door

419
00:27:22,771 --> 00:27:24,563
<i>Dump the crooks in a boiling bowl

420
00:27:24,564 --> 00:27:26,357
<i>Pound them up with a thumping pole

421
00:27:26,358 --> 00:27:27,274
<i>When you're finished

422
00:27:27,275 --> 00:27:31,445
<i>If they are whole

423
00:27:31,446 --> 00:27:36,446
<i>Send them down the hall to roll

424
00:27:41,665 --> 00:27:43,624
<i>That's what Bilbo Baggins hates

425
00:27:46,419 --> 00:27:50,339
Bilbo.

426
00:27:57,389 --> 00:28:02,389
He is here.

427
00:28:03,144 --> 00:28:06,105
Gandalf.

428
00:28:06,106 --> 00:28:07,147
I thought you said...

429
00:28:07,148 --> 00:28:08,440
...this place would be easy...

430
00:28:08,441 --> 00:28:11,193
...to find. I lost my way, twice.

431
00:28:11,194 --> 00:28:14,863
I wouldn't have found it at all
had it not been for that mark on the door.

432
00:28:14,864 --> 00:28:17,992
Mark? There's no mark on that door.
It was painted a week ago.

433
00:28:17,993 --> 00:28:21,829
There is a mark. I put it there myself.

434
00:28:21,830 --> 00:28:26,500
Bilbo Baggins, allow me to introduce
the leader of our company...

435
00:28:26,501 --> 00:28:28,669
...Thorin Oakenshield.

436
00:28:28,670 --> 00:28:31,714
So...

437
00:28:31,715 --> 00:28:34,466
...this is the Hobbit.

438
00:28:34,467 --> 00:28:37,011
Tell me, Mr. Baggins,
have you done much fighting?

439
00:28:37,012 --> 00:28:39,138
- Pardon me?
- Ax or sword?

440
00:28:39,139 --> 00:28:40,848
What's your weapon of choice?

441
00:28:40,849 --> 00:28:44,518
Well, I do have some skill at conkers,
if you must know...

442
00:28:44,519 --> 00:28:48,480
...but I fail to see why that's relevant.

443
00:28:48,481 --> 00:28:50,274
Thought as much.

444
00:28:50,275 --> 00:28:53,277
He looks more like a grocer than a burglar.

445
00:28:58,283 --> 00:28:59,199
What news...

446
00:28:59,200 --> 00:29:02,202
...from the meeting in Ered Luin?
Did they all come?

447
00:29:02,203 --> 00:29:05,456
- Aye. Envoys from all seven kingdoms.
- All of them!

448
00:29:05,457 --> 00:29:09,168
And what did the Dwarves
of the Iron Hills say?

449
00:29:09,169 --> 00:29:13,464
Is Dain with us?

450
00:29:13,465 --> 00:29:15,132
They will not come.

451
00:29:18,011 --> 00:29:19,261
They say this quest...

452
00:29:19,262 --> 00:29:24,262
...is ours and ours alone.

453
00:29:24,601 --> 00:29:27,811
You're going on a quest?

454
00:29:27,812 --> 00:29:32,812
Bilbo, my dear fellow,
let us have a little more light.

455
00:29:33,651 --> 00:29:36,028
Far to the east...

456
00:29:36,029 --> 00:29:39,073
...over ranges and rivers...

457
00:29:39,074 --> 00:29:42,576
...beyond woodlands and wastelands...

458
00:29:42,577 --> 00:29:47,577
...lies a single, solitary peak.

459
00:29:48,416 --> 00:29:50,834
"The Lonely Mountain".

460
00:29:50,835 --> 00:29:53,170
Aye, Oin has read...

461
00:29:53,171 --> 00:29:57,841
...the portents,
and the portents say it is time.

462
00:29:57,842 --> 00:29:59,093
Ravens have been seen...

463
00:29:59,094 --> 00:30:02,888
...flying back to the mountain,
as it was foretold.

464
00:30:02,889 --> 00:30:05,682
"When the birds of yore return...

465
00:30:05,683 --> 00:30:07,017
...to Erebor...

466
00:30:07,018 --> 00:30:08,769
...the reign of the beast...

467
00:30:08,770 --> 00:30:13,565
...will end."

468
00:30:13,566 --> 00:30:15,943
- Uh, what beast?
- That would be a reference...

469
00:30:15,944 --> 00:30:17,444
...to Smaug the Terrible...

470
00:30:17,445 --> 00:30:18,946
...chiefest and greatest...

471
00:30:18,947 --> 00:30:22,116
...calamity of our age.

472
00:30:22,117 --> 00:30:24,034
Airborne fire-breather.

473
00:30:24,035 --> 00:30:25,285
Teeth like razors...

474
00:30:25,286 --> 00:30:26,995
...claws like meat hooks.

475
00:30:26,996 --> 00:30:28,539
Fond of precious metals.

476
00:30:28,540 --> 00:30:29,998
Yes, I know what a dragon is.

477
00:30:29,999 --> 00:30:31,959
I'm not afraid. I'm up for it.

478
00:30:31,960 --> 00:30:34,962
I'll give him a taste of Dwarfish iron
right up his jacksie!

479
00:30:34,963 --> 00:30:35,879
Good lad, Ori!

480
00:30:35,880 --> 00:30:36,797
Sit down.

481
00:30:36,798 --> 00:30:38,215
The task would be difficult...

482
00:30:38,216 --> 00:30:39,842
...with an army behind us...

483
00:30:39,843 --> 00:30:42,177
...but we number just 13.

484
00:30:42,178 --> 00:30:44,680
And not 13 of the best...

485
00:30:44,681 --> 00:30:46,306
...nor brightest.

486
00:30:46,307 --> 00:30:48,642
Here, who are you calling dim?

487
00:30:48,643 --> 00:30:50,352
Sorry, what did he say?

488
00:30:50,353 --> 00:30:53,021
We may be few in number...

489
00:30:53,022 --> 00:30:56,275
...but we're fighters, all of us...

490
00:30:56,276 --> 00:30:57,526
...to the last Dwarf.

491
00:30:57,527 --> 00:30:59,945
And you forget,
we have a Wizard in our company.

492
00:30:59,946 --> 00:31:02,531
Gandalf will have killed
hundreds of dragons.

493
00:31:02,532 --> 00:31:04,700
Oh, well, no. I wouldn't say...

494
00:31:04,701 --> 00:31:06,869
- How many, then?
- What?

495
00:31:06,870 --> 00:31:09,913
How many dragons have you killed?

496
00:31:11,207 --> 00:31:12,332
Go on.

497
00:31:12,333 --> 00:31:14,084
Give us a number.

498
00:31:16,212 --> 00:31:18,380
Excuse me. Please.

499
00:31:18,381 --> 00:31:22,217
<font color=#FF8000>Atk√¢t!</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(Silence!)</font>

500
00:31:22,218 --> 00:31:23,844
If we have read these signs...

501
00:31:23,845 --> 00:31:28,807
...do you not think others
will have read them too?

502
00:31:28,808 --> 00:31:31,768
Rumors have begun to spread.

503
00:31:31,769 --> 00:31:36,106
The dragon, Smaug,
has not been seen for 60 years.

504
00:31:36,107 --> 00:31:39,234
Eyes look east to the mountain, assessing...

505
00:31:39,235 --> 00:31:42,946
...wondering, weighing the risk.

506
00:31:42,947 --> 00:31:45,949
Perhaps the vast wealth of our people
now lies unprotected.

507
00:31:45,950 --> 00:31:50,120
Do we sit back while others claim
what is rightfully ours?

508
00:31:50,121 --> 00:31:52,289
Or do we seize this chance...

509
00:31:52,290 --> 00:31:53,248
...to take back Erebor?

510
00:31:53,249 --> 00:31:55,292
<font color=#FF8000>Du Bek√¢r! Du Bek√¢r!</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(To arms! To arms!)</font>

511
00:31:55,293 --> 00:31:58,503
You forget, the Front Gate is sealed.

512
00:31:58,504 --> 00:31:59,630
There is no way...

513
00:31:59,631 --> 00:32:01,757
...into the mountain.

514
00:32:01,758 --> 00:32:06,758
That, my dear Balin, is not entirely true.

515
00:32:09,057 --> 00:32:11,016
How came you by this?

516
00:32:11,017 --> 00:32:12,267
It was given to me...

517
00:32:12,268 --> 00:32:14,102
...by your father.

518
00:32:14,103 --> 00:32:15,854
By Thrain.

519
00:32:15,855 --> 00:32:18,190
For safekeeping.

520
00:32:18,191 --> 00:32:19,149
It is yours...

521
00:32:19,150 --> 00:32:24,150
...now.

522
00:32:27,659 --> 00:32:30,077
If there is a key...

523
00:32:30,078 --> 00:32:32,287
...there must be a door.

524
00:32:32,288 --> 00:32:33,205
These runes...

525
00:32:33,206 --> 00:32:37,000
...speak of a hidden passage
to the Lower Halls.

526
00:32:37,001 --> 00:32:39,336
There's another way in.

527
00:32:39,337 --> 00:32:43,340
Well, if we can find it,
but Dwarf doors are invisible when closed.

528
00:32:45,468 --> 00:32:48,512
The answer lies hidden somewhere
in this map...

529
00:32:48,513 --> 00:32:50,722
...and I do not have the skill to find it.

530
00:32:50,723 --> 00:32:55,723
But there are others in Middle-earth
who can.

531
00:32:55,853 --> 00:32:59,398
The task I have in mind
will require a great deal of stealth...

532
00:32:59,399 --> 00:33:03,235
...and no small amount of courage.

533
00:33:03,236 --> 00:33:07,614
But if we are careful and clever,
I believe that it can be done.

534
00:33:07,615 --> 00:33:09,491
That's why we need a burglar.

535
00:33:09,492 --> 00:33:13,161
Hmm. And a good one too.
An expert, I'd imagine.

536
00:33:13,162 --> 00:33:17,874
And are you?

537
00:33:17,875 --> 00:33:19,501
Am I what?

538
00:33:19,502 --> 00:33:22,754
He said he's an expert. Hey.

539
00:33:22,755 --> 00:33:27,755
Me? No. No, no, no. I'm not a burglar.
I've never stolen a thing in my life.

540
00:33:27,802 --> 00:33:30,679
Well, I'm afraid I have to agree
with Mr. Baggins.

541
00:33:30,680 --> 00:33:32,889
He's hardly burglar material.

542
00:33:32,890 --> 00:33:34,558
Nope.

543
00:33:34,559 --> 00:33:38,562
Aye, the Wild is no place for gentle folk
who can neither fight nor fend for themselves.

544
00:33:38,563 --> 00:33:40,897
He's just fine.

545
00:33:45,987 --> 00:33:47,404
Enough!

546
00:33:47,405 --> 00:33:49,197
If I say Bilbo Baggins...

547
00:33:49,198 --> 00:33:50,907
...is a burglar, then a burglar...

548
00:33:50,908 --> 00:33:53,910
...he is.

549
00:33:53,911 --> 00:33:55,370
Hobbits are light...

550
00:33:55,371 --> 00:33:59,750
...on their feet. In fact, they can pass
unseen by most, if they choose.

551
00:33:59,751 --> 00:34:03,545
And, while the dragon is accustomed
to the smell of Dwarf...

552
00:34:03,546 --> 00:34:06,006
...the scent of a Hobbit is all but...

553
00:34:06,007 --> 00:34:10,135
...unknown to him,
which gives us a distinct advantage.

554
00:34:10,136 --> 00:34:13,013
You asked me to find
the 14th member of this company...

555
00:34:13,014 --> 00:34:14,806
...and I have chosen Mr. Baggins.

556
00:34:14,807 --> 00:34:16,224
There's more to him...

557
00:34:16,225 --> 00:34:17,934
...than appearances suggest.

558
00:34:17,935 --> 00:34:22,356
And he's got a great deal more to offer
than any of you know.

559
00:34:22,357 --> 00:34:27,357
Including himself.

560
00:34:29,447 --> 00:34:34,447
You must trust me on this.

561
00:34:34,994 --> 00:34:36,661
Very well.

562
00:34:36,662 --> 00:34:38,455
- We will do it your way.
- No, no.

563
00:34:38,456 --> 00:34:41,041
- Give him the contract.
- We're in. We're off.

564
00:34:41,042 --> 00:34:43,168
It's just the usual. Summary...

565
00:34:43,169 --> 00:34:45,253
...of out-of-pocket expenses,
time required...

566
00:34:45,254 --> 00:34:46,254
...remuneration...

567
00:34:46,255 --> 00:34:49,007
...funeral arrangements, so forth.

568
00:34:49,008 --> 00:34:53,387
Funeral arrangements?

569
00:34:56,182 --> 00:34:58,392
I cannot guarantee his safety.

570
00:34:58,393 --> 00:35:00,102
Understood.

571
00:35:00,103 --> 00:35:05,103
Nor will I be responsible for his fate.

572
00:35:06,567 --> 00:35:08,068
Agreed.

573
00:35:08,069 --> 00:35:08,985
"Terms: Cash on...

574
00:35:08,986 --> 00:35:12,823
...delivery, up to but not exceeding
one-fourteenth of total profit, if any."

575
00:35:12,824 --> 00:35:14,866
Hmm. Seems fair.

576
00:35:14,867 --> 00:35:18,745
"Present company shall not be liable
for injuries inflicted by...

577
00:35:18,746 --> 00:35:23,746
...or sustained as a consequence thereof,
including, but not limited to lacerations...

578
00:35:25,378 --> 00:35:29,673
...evisceration..."

579
00:35:29,674 --> 00:35:31,883
- Incineration?
- Aye.

580
00:35:31,884 --> 00:35:36,884
He'll melt the flesh off your bones
in the blink of an eye.

581
00:35:39,100 --> 00:35:40,475
You all right, laddie?

582
00:35:40,476 --> 00:35:43,770
Huh? Yeah.

583
00:35:43,771 --> 00:35:45,522
Feel a bit faint.

584
00:35:45,523 --> 00:35:47,691
- Think furnace with wings.
- Air.

585
00:35:47,692 --> 00:35:49,317
I need air.

586
00:35:49,318 --> 00:35:51,486
Flash of light, searing pain, then...

587
00:35:51,487 --> 00:35:54,239
...poof. You're nothing more than a pile of ash.

588
00:35:54,240 --> 00:35:59,240
Hmm.

589
00:36:00,413 --> 00:36:02,664
Nope.

590
00:36:02,665 --> 00:36:04,875
Oh, very helpful, Bofur.

591
00:36:04,876 --> 00:36:08,170
I'll be all right.
Just let me sit quietly for a moment.

592
00:36:08,171 --> 00:36:11,256
You've been sitting quietly for far too long.

593
00:36:11,257 --> 00:36:13,091
Tell me...

594
00:36:13,092 --> 00:36:15,594
...when did doilies
and your mother's dishes...

595
00:36:15,595 --> 00:36:17,804
...become so important to you?

596
00:36:17,805 --> 00:36:22,805
I remember a young Hobbit who was always
running off in search of Elves in the woods.

597
00:36:22,810 --> 00:36:26,146
Who would stay out late,
come home after dark...

598
00:36:26,147 --> 00:36:29,941
...trailing mud and twigs and fireflies.

599
00:36:29,942 --> 00:36:32,611
A young Hobbit who would have liked
nothing better...

600
00:36:32,612 --> 00:36:36,531
...than to find out what was beyond
the borders of the Shire.

601
00:36:36,532 --> 00:36:37,449
The world...

602
00:36:37,450 --> 00:36:41,369
...is not in your books and maps.

603
00:36:41,370 --> 00:36:42,287
It's out...

604
00:36:42,288 --> 00:36:45,248
...there.

605
00:36:45,249 --> 00:36:47,709
I can't just go running off into the blue.

606
00:36:47,710 --> 00:36:51,046
I am a Baggins of Bag-end.

607
00:36:51,047 --> 00:36:54,883
You are also a Took.

608
00:36:54,884 --> 00:36:55,842
Did you know...

609
00:36:55,843 --> 00:36:57,552
...that your great-great-great-great-uncle...

610
00:36:57,553 --> 00:36:59,930
...Bullroarer Took was so large...

611
00:36:59,931 --> 00:37:01,473
...he could ride a real horse?

612
00:37:01,474 --> 00:37:02,641
- Yes.
- Yes...

613
00:37:02,642 --> 00:37:03,808
...well, he could.

614
00:37:03,809 --> 00:37:06,853
In the Battle of Green Fields,
he charged the Goblin ranks.

615
00:37:06,854 --> 00:37:10,857
He swung his club so hard,
it knocked the Goblin king's head clean off...

616
00:37:10,858 --> 00:37:15,237
...and it sailed 100 yards through the air
and went down a rabbit hole.

617
00:37:15,238 --> 00:37:17,697
And thus, the battle was won.

618
00:37:17,698 --> 00:37:22,698
And the game of golf invented
at the same time.

619
00:37:23,829 --> 00:37:26,289
I do believe you made that up.

620
00:37:26,290 --> 00:37:31,290
Well, all good stories
deserve embellishment.

621
00:37:31,504 --> 00:37:36,504
You'll have a tale or two to tell of your own
when you come back.

622
00:37:39,220 --> 00:37:43,390
Can you promise that I will come back?

623
00:37:43,391 --> 00:37:45,141
No.

624
00:37:45,142 --> 00:37:47,978
And if you do...

625
00:37:47,979 --> 00:37:51,856
...you will not be the same.

626
00:37:51,857 --> 00:37:54,693
That's what I thought.

627
00:37:54,694 --> 00:37:59,364
Sorry, Gandalf, I can't sign this.

628
00:37:59,365 --> 00:38:04,365
You've got the wrong Hobbit.

629
00:38:08,082 --> 00:38:12,711
It appears we have lost our burglar.

630
00:38:12,712 --> 00:38:14,921
Probably for the best.

631
00:38:14,922 --> 00:38:17,465
The odds were always against us.

632
00:38:17,466 --> 00:38:20,969
After all, what are we?

633
00:38:20,970 --> 00:38:24,389
Merchants, miners...

634
00:38:24,390 --> 00:38:26,766
...tinkers, toy-makers.

635
00:38:26,767 --> 00:38:30,186
Heh, heh. Hardly the stuff of legend.

636
00:38:30,187 --> 00:38:33,690
There are a few warriors amongst us.

637
00:38:33,691 --> 00:38:35,775
Old warriors.

638
00:38:35,776 --> 00:38:38,361
I would take each and every one
of these Dwarves...

639
00:38:38,362 --> 00:38:40,655
...over an army from the Iron Hills.

640
00:38:40,656 --> 00:38:44,326
For when I called upon them,
they answered.

641
00:38:44,327 --> 00:38:47,287
Loyalty, honor...

642
00:38:47,288 --> 00:38:50,707
...a willing heart.

643
00:38:50,708 --> 00:38:53,627
I can ask no more than that.

644
00:38:53,628 --> 00:38:54,544
You don't...

645
00:38:54,545 --> 00:38:56,463
...have to do this.

646
00:38:56,464 --> 00:38:58,298
You have a choice.

647
00:38:58,299 --> 00:39:02,093
You've done honorably by our people.

648
00:39:02,094 --> 00:39:06,181
You have built a new life for us
in the Blue Mountains.

649
00:39:06,182 --> 00:39:07,474
A life of peace...

650
00:39:07,475 --> 00:39:10,060
...and plenty.

651
00:39:10,061 --> 00:39:15,061
A life that is worth more than
all the gold in Erebor.

652
00:39:15,566 --> 00:39:20,566
From my grandfather to my father,
this has come to me.

653
00:39:21,781 --> 00:39:23,239
They dreamt of the day...

654
00:39:23,240 --> 00:39:27,827
...when the Dwarves of Erebor
would reclaim their homeland.

655
00:39:27,828 --> 00:39:31,706
There is no choice, Balin.

656
00:39:31,707 --> 00:39:35,669
Not for me.

657
00:39:35,670 --> 00:39:39,964
Then we are with you, laddie.

658
00:39:39,965 --> 00:39:44,886
We will see it done.

659
00:40:03,698 --> 00:40:07,200
<i>Far over

660
00:40:07,201 --> 00:40:12,201
<i>The misty mountains cold

661
00:40:12,665 --> 00:40:17,168
<i>To dungeons deep

662
00:40:17,169 --> 00:40:21,840
<i>And caverns old

663
00:40:21,841 --> 00:40:26,553
<i>We must away

664
00:40:26,554 --> 00:40:31,516
<i>'Ere break of day

665
00:40:31,517 --> 00:40:35,270
<i>To find our

666
00:40:35,271 --> 00:40:40,233
<i>Long-forgotten gold

667
00:40:40,234 --> 00:40:43,987
<i>The pines were roaring

668
00:40:43,988 --> 00:40:48,988
<i>On the height

669
00:40:49,285 --> 00:40:50,285
<i>The winds

670
00:40:50,286 --> 00:40:53,246
<i>Were moaning

671
00:40:53,247 --> 00:40:58,247
<i>In the night

672
00:40:58,252 --> 00:41:02,714
<i>The fire was red

673
00:41:02,715 --> 00:41:07,469
<i>It flaming spread

674
00:41:07,470 --> 00:41:11,306
<i>The trees like torches

675
00:41:11,307 --> 00:41:16,307
<i>Blazed With light

676
00:41:55,434 --> 00:42:00,434
Hello?

677
00:42:07,321 --> 00:42:08,988
Yes.

678
00:42:08,989 --> 00:42:13,989
Yes.

679
00:43:22,938 --> 00:43:24,105
Here...

680
00:43:24,106 --> 00:43:26,024
...Mr. Bilbo, where are you off to?

681
00:43:26,025 --> 00:43:28,610
- Can't stop, I'm already late!
- Late for what?

682
00:43:28,611 --> 00:43:33,611
I'm going on an adventure!

683
00:43:37,119 --> 00:43:40,747
I said it. Didn't I say it?
Corning here was a waste of time.

684
00:43:40,748 --> 00:43:42,498
That's true enough.

685
00:43:42,499 --> 00:43:45,543
Ridiculous notion. Use a Hobbit?
A Halfling?

686
00:43:45,544 --> 00:43:47,128
Whose idea was it anyway?

687
00:43:47,129 --> 00:43:49,005
Wait!

688
00:43:49,006 --> 00:43:50,256
Wait!

689
00:43:50,257 --> 00:43:52,008
Whoa, whoa.

690
00:43:53,510 --> 00:43:58,510
Whoa, whoa.

691
00:44:01,268 --> 00:44:04,562
I signed it.

692
00:44:04,563 --> 00:44:09,563
Here.

693
00:44:14,990 --> 00:44:16,282
Everything appears...

694
00:44:16,283 --> 00:44:17,909
...to be in order.

695
00:44:17,910 --> 00:44:20,870
Welcome, Master Baggins...

696
00:44:20,871 --> 00:44:24,707
...to the company of Thorin Oakenshield.

697
00:44:29,838 --> 00:44:31,464
Give him a pony.

698
00:44:31,465 --> 00:44:33,257
No, no, that won't be necessary.

699
00:44:33,258 --> 00:44:35,635
Thank you. I'm sure I can keep up on foot.

700
00:44:35,636 --> 00:44:38,388
I've done my fair share of walking holidays,
you know?

701
00:44:38,389 --> 00:44:43,389
Even got as far as Frogmorton once. Aah!

702
00:44:54,321 --> 00:44:58,199
Come on, Nori. Pay up.

703
00:44:58,200 --> 00:45:00,451
- One more.
- ks, lad.

704
00:45:00,452 --> 00:45:02,203
What's that about?

705
00:45:02,204 --> 00:45:06,916
Oh, they took wagers
on whether or not you'd turn up.

706
00:45:06,917 --> 00:45:11,087
Most of them bet that you wouldn't.

707
00:45:11,088 --> 00:45:12,880
And what did you think?

708
00:45:12,881 --> 00:45:17,468
Well...

709
00:45:17,469 --> 00:45:22,469
My dear fellow,
I never doubted you for a second.

710
00:45:26,937 --> 00:45:31,107
It's horse hair. Having a reaction.

711
00:45:32,484 --> 00:45:34,736
No, wait, wait, stop.

712
00:45:34,737 --> 00:45:37,155
Stop! We have to turn around.

713
00:45:37,156 --> 00:45:38,322
What on earth...

714
00:45:38,323 --> 00:45:39,365
...is the matter?

715
00:45:39,366 --> 00:45:43,161
- I forgot my handkerchief.
- Here.

716
00:45:43,162 --> 00:45:47,123
Use this.

717
00:45:48,625 --> 00:45:53,625
Move on.

718
00:45:57,301 --> 00:46:00,303
<i>You'll have to manage
without pocket handkerchiefs...

719
00:46:00,304 --> 00:46:02,805
<i>...and a good many other things,
Bilbo Baggins...

720
00:46:02,806 --> 00:46:06,768
<i>...before we reach our journey's end.

721
00:46:06,769 --> 00:46:07,769
<i>You were born...

722
00:46:07,770 --> 00:46:12,770
<i>...to the rolling hills
and little rivers of the Shire.

723
00:46:13,192 --> 00:46:16,277
<i>But home is now behind you.

724
00:46:16,278 --> 00:46:21,278
<i>The world is ahead.

725
00:47:00,030 --> 00:47:05,030
Hello, girl. Who's a good girl?

726
00:47:06,995 --> 00:47:09,122
It's our little secret, Myrtle.

727
00:47:09,123 --> 00:47:11,290
You must tell no one. Shh, shh.

728
00:47:15,796 --> 00:47:18,214
What was that?

729
00:47:18,215 --> 00:47:19,966
<i>Orcs.

730
00:47:19,967 --> 00:47:22,677
Orcs?

731
00:47:22,678 --> 00:47:23,719
Throat-cutters.

732
00:47:23,720 --> 00:47:25,805
There'll be dozens of them out there.

733
00:47:25,806 --> 00:47:26,848
The lone-lands...

734
00:47:26,849 --> 00:47:29,016
...are crawling with them.
- They strike...

735
00:47:29,017 --> 00:47:33,062
...in the wee small hours when everyone's
asleep. Quick and quiet, no screams.

736
00:47:33,063 --> 00:47:37,608
Just lots of blood.

737
00:47:38,902 --> 00:47:42,446
You think that's funny?

738
00:47:42,447 --> 00:47:45,616
You think a night raid by Orcs is a joke?

739
00:47:45,617 --> 00:47:48,244
We didn't mean anything by it.

740
00:47:48,245 --> 00:47:50,329
No, you didn't.

741
00:47:50,330 --> 00:47:54,292
You know nothing of the world.

742
00:47:54,293 --> 00:47:56,711
Don't mind him, laddie.

743
00:47:56,712 --> 00:48:01,712
Thorin has more cause than most
to hate Orcs.

744
00:48:06,054 --> 00:48:09,473
After the dragon took the Lonely Mountain...

745
00:48:09,474 --> 00:48:10,766
...King Thror...

746
00:48:10,767 --> 00:48:15,767
...tried to reclaim
the ancient Dwarf kingdom of Moria.

747
00:48:17,149 --> 00:48:22,149
<i>But our enemy had got there first.

748
00:48:32,748 --> 00:48:37,501
<i>Moria had been taken by legions of Orcs...

749
00:48:37,502 --> 00:48:39,587
<i>...led by the most vile...

750
00:48:39,588 --> 00:48:42,173
<i>...of all their race...

751
00:48:42,174 --> 00:48:43,000
<i>Azog...

752
00:48:43,100 --> 00:48:44,500
<font color=#FF0000>Goryagug!</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(You will all die!)</font>

753
00:48:44,593 --> 00:48:47,595
<i>...the Defiler.

754
00:48:47,596 --> 00:48:50,765
<i>The giant Gundabad Orc...

755
00:48:50,766 --> 00:48:55,766
...had sworn to wipe out the line of Durin.

756
00:48:59,942 --> 00:49:02,777
He began...

757
00:49:02,778 --> 00:49:04,862
...by beheading the king.

758
00:49:16,041 --> 00:49:20,127
No!

759
00:49:20,128 --> 00:49:22,380
Thrain, Thorin's father...

760
00:49:22,381 --> 00:49:25,174
...was driven mad by grief.

761
00:49:25,175 --> 00:49:28,386
He went missing. Taken prisoner or killed...

762
00:49:28,387 --> 00:49:31,305
...we did not know.

763
00:49:31,306 --> 00:49:33,557
We were leaderless.

764
00:49:33,558 --> 00:49:37,311
<i>Defeat and death...

765
00:49:37,312 --> 00:49:42,066
<i>...were upon us.

766
00:49:42,067 --> 00:49:47,067
That is when I saw him.

767
00:49:48,156 --> 00:49:50,825
A young Dwarf prince...

768
00:49:50,826 --> 00:49:52,451
<i>...facing down...

769
00:49:52,452 --> 00:49:57,452
<i>...the pale Orc.

770
00:49:58,709 --> 00:50:00,251
<i>He stood alone...

771
00:50:00,252 --> 00:50:02,545
<i>...against this terrible foe.

772
00:50:12,055 --> 00:50:13,889
<i>His armor rent...

773
00:50:13,890 --> 00:50:14,849
...wielding nothing...

774
00:50:14,850 --> 00:50:16,600
<i>...but an oaken branch...

775
00:50:16,601 --> 00:50:21,601
<i>...as a shield.

776
00:50:30,407 --> 00:50:31,407
<i>Azog...

777
00:50:31,408 --> 00:50:35,661
<i>...the Defiler learned that day...

778
00:50:35,662 --> 00:50:40,662
...that the line of Durin
would not be so easily broken.

779
00:50:43,400 --> 00:50:51,600
