Where on...

834
00:57:37,375 --> 00:57:41,170
...this good earth
did those foul creatures come from?

835
00:57:43,173 --> 00:57:45,466
The old fortress?

836
00:57:45,467 --> 00:57:47,000
Show me.

837
00:58:20,251 --> 00:58:22,461
We'll camp here for the night.

838
00:58:22,462 --> 00:58:27,090
Fili, Kili, look after the ponies.
Make sure you stay with them.

839
00:58:27,091 --> 00:58:31,345
A farmer and his family used to live here.

840
00:58:31,346 --> 00:58:34,306
- Oin, Gloin. Get a fire going.
- Aye.

841
00:58:34,307 --> 00:58:35,516
Right you are.

842
00:58:35,517 --> 00:58:40,103
I think it would be wiser to move on.

843
00:58:40,104 --> 00:58:43,273
We could make for the Hidden Valley.

844
00:58:43,274 --> 00:58:45,359
I have told you already...

845
00:58:45,360 --> 00:58:47,402
...I will not go near that place.

846
00:58:47,403 --> 00:58:49,863
Why not? The Elves could help us.

847
00:58:49,864 --> 00:58:52,115
We could get food, rest, advice.

848
00:58:52,116 --> 00:58:55,536
- I do not need their advice.
- We have a map...

849
00:58:55,537 --> 00:58:58,622
...that we cannot read.
Lord Elrond could help us.

850
00:58:58,623 --> 00:59:00,999
Help?

851
00:59:01,000 --> 00:59:03,293
A dragon attacks Erebor.

852
00:59:03,294 --> 00:59:06,588
What help came from the Elves?

853
00:59:06,589 --> 00:59:08,715
Orcs plunder Moria...

854
00:59:08,716 --> 00:59:12,427
...desecrate our sacred halls.
The Elves looked on...

855
00:59:12,428 --> 00:59:15,138
...and did nothing.

856
00:59:15,139 --> 00:59:19,393
And you ask me to seek out the very people
who betrayed my grandfather.

857
00:59:19,394 --> 00:59:20,853
Who betrayed my father.

858
00:59:20,854 --> 00:59:23,397
You are neither of them.

859
00:59:23,398 --> 00:59:24,314
I did not...

860
00:59:24,315 --> 00:59:27,276
...give you that map and key
for you to hold onto the past.

861
00:59:27,277 --> 00:59:32,277
I did not know
that they were yours to keep.

862
00:59:35,410 --> 00:59:38,328
Everything all right?
Gandalf, where are you going?

863
00:59:38,329 --> 00:59:41,915
To seek the company of the
only one around here who's got any sense.

864
00:59:41,916 --> 00:59:42,875
And who's that?

865
00:59:42,876 --> 00:59:45,002
Myself, Mr. Baggins.

866
00:59:45,003 --> 00:59:49,423
I've had enough of Dwarves for one day.

867
00:59:49,424 --> 00:59:52,050
Come on, Bombur, we're hungry.

868
00:59:52,051 --> 00:59:57,051
Is he coming back?

869
00:59:58,641 --> 01:00:00,142
He's been a long time.

870
01:00:00,143 --> 01:00:01,602
- Who?
- Gandalf.

871
01:00:01,603 --> 01:00:03,937
He's a Wizard. He does as he chooses.

872
01:00:03,938 --> 01:00:07,524
Here, do us a favor. Take this to the lads.

873
01:00:07,525 --> 01:00:09,276
Stop it. You've had plenty.

874
01:00:09,277 --> 01:00:13,113
Aye, it's not a bad stew, Bombur.
I've had worse.

875
01:00:13,114 --> 01:00:15,324
Dori could've cooked it. Ha-ha-ha.

876
01:00:15,325 --> 01:00:20,325
Hilarious.

877
01:00:28,212 --> 01:00:29,713
What's the matter?

878
01:00:29,714 --> 01:00:34,301
- We're supposed to be looking after the ponies.
- Only we've encountered a slight problem.

879
01:00:34,302 --> 01:00:36,386
We had 16.

880
01:00:36,387 --> 01:00:41,387
Now there's 14.

881
01:00:42,518 --> 01:00:45,020
Daisy and Bungo are missing.

882
01:00:45,021 --> 01:00:46,939
Well, that's not good. Ha, ha.

883
01:00:46,940 --> 01:00:49,733
And that is not good at all.
Shouldn't we tell Thorin?

884
01:00:49,734 --> 01:00:52,819
Uh, no. Let's not worry him.

885
01:00:52,820 --> 01:00:56,239
As our official burglar,
we thought you might like to look into it.

886
01:00:56,240 --> 01:00:58,116
Well, uh...

887
01:00:58,117 --> 01:01:02,496
- Look, something big uprooted these trees.
- That was our thinking.

888
01:01:02,497 --> 01:01:07,497
It's something very big
and possibly quite dangerous.

889
01:01:07,794 --> 01:01:09,419
Hey...

890
01:01:09,420 --> 01:01:11,588
There's a light.

891
01:01:11,589 --> 01:01:15,509
Over here.

892
01:01:15,510 --> 01:01:18,220
Stay down.

893
01:01:22,016 --> 01:01:23,642
What is it?

894
01:01:23,643 --> 01:01:28,643
Trolls.

895
01:01:43,371 --> 01:01:44,621
Oh.

896
01:01:51,963 --> 01:01:56,963
He's got Myrtle and Minty. I think they're
gonna eat them. We have to do something.

897
01:01:58,011 --> 01:02:00,053
Yes, you should.

898
01:02:00,054 --> 01:02:01,680
Mountain Trolls are slow...

899
01:02:01,681 --> 01:02:04,307
...and stupid, and you're small,
they'll never see you.

900
01:02:04,308 --> 01:02:06,476
It's perfectly safe. We'll be behind you.

901
01:02:06,477 --> 01:02:08,603
If you run into trouble,
hoot twice like a barn owl...

902
01:02:08,604 --> 01:02:10,188
...and once like a brown owl.

903
01:02:10,189 --> 01:02:13,275
 Twice like a barn owl.
No, twice like a brown... Once like a...

904
01:02:13,276 --> 01:02:15,652
Like a... Are you sure this is a good idea?

905
01:02:15,653 --> 01:02:18,864
Mutton yesterday, mutton today...

906
01:02:18,865 --> 01:02:23,452
...and, blimey, if it don't look like
mutton again tomorrow.

907
01:02:23,453 --> 01:02:25,620
Quit your griping.

908
01:02:25,621 --> 01:02:30,042
These ain't sheep. These is fresh nags.

909
01:02:30,043 --> 01:02:34,421
Oh! I don't like horse. I never have.

910
01:02:34,422 --> 01:02:36,715
- Not enough fat on them.
- Well, it's better...

911
01:02:36,716 --> 01:02:39,593
...than leathery old farmer.
All skin and bone, he was.

912
01:02:39,594 --> 01:02:40,761
I'm still picking...

913
01:02:40,762 --> 01:02:42,596
...bits of him out of me teeth.

914
01:02:43,765 --> 01:02:47,100
Well, that's lovely, that is. A floater.

915
01:02:47,101 --> 01:02:49,227
Might improve the flavor.

916
01:02:49,228 --> 01:02:51,980
Ah. There's more where that came from.

917
01:02:51,981 --> 01:02:53,523
- Oh, no, you don't!
- Ow!

918
01:02:57,111 --> 01:03:00,906
Sit down!

919
01:03:07,163 --> 01:03:11,583
Well, I hope you're gonna gut these nags.

920
01:03:11,584 --> 01:03:14,586
I don't like the stinky parts.

921
01:03:14,587 --> 01:03:17,589
- Ow!
- I said sit down.

922
01:03:17,590 --> 01:03:18,799
I'm starving!

923
01:03:18,800 --> 01:03:22,052
Now, are we having horse tonight or what?

924
01:03:22,053 --> 01:03:24,179
Shut your cakehole.

925
01:03:24,180 --> 01:03:26,973
You'll eat what I give you.

926
01:03:26,974 --> 01:03:30,852
How come he's the cook?
Everything tastes the same.

927
01:03:30,853 --> 01:03:32,604
Everything tastes like chicken.

928
01:03:32,605 --> 01:03:34,022
Except the chicken.

929
01:03:34,023 --> 01:03:35,482
What tastes like fish!

930
01:03:35,483 --> 01:03:38,735
I'm just saying,
a little appreciation would be nice.

931
01:03:41,114 --> 01:03:43,740
Oh. "Thank you very much, Bert.

932
01:03:43,741 --> 01:03:45,117
Lovely stew, Bert."

933
01:03:45,118 --> 01:03:49,371
- How hard is that?
- Shh. Shh, shh. Shh.

934
01:03:49,372 --> 01:03:50,330
Just needs...

935
01:03:50,331 --> 01:03:53,375
...a sprinkle of squirrel dung.

936
01:03:53,376 --> 01:03:54,292
Here...

937
01:03:54,293 --> 01:03:55,544
...that's my grog.

938
01:03:58,005 --> 01:04:02,884
Sorry. Ow!

939
01:04:02,885 --> 01:04:07,681
Ooh. That is beautifully balanced, that is.

940
01:04:07,682 --> 01:04:11,601
Wrap your laughing gear around that, eh?

941
01:04:11,602 --> 01:04:13,019
Good, isn't it?

942
01:04:14,564 --> 01:04:17,607
That's why I'm the cook.

943
01:04:24,907 --> 01:04:29,327
Oh, me guts are grumbling.
I got to snaffle something.

944
01:04:29,328 --> 01:04:32,581
- Flesh, I need flesh.
- Ah! Ah!

945
01:04:35,501 --> 01:04:37,294
Blimey!

946
01:04:37,295 --> 01:04:40,380
Bert. Bert!
Look what's come out of me hooter.

947
01:04:40,381 --> 01:04:42,799
It's got arms and legs and everything.

948
01:04:42,800 --> 01:04:45,218
- What is it?
- I don't know.

949
01:04:45,219 --> 01:04:50,219
I don't like the way it wriggles around.

950
01:04:51,100 --> 01:04:54,519
What are you, then? An oversized squirrel?

951
01:04:54,520 --> 01:04:56,396
I'm a burglar... Uh, Hobbit.

952
01:04:56,397 --> 01:04:58,648
A burglar Hobbit?

953
01:04:58,649 --> 01:05:00,442
Can we cook him?

954
01:05:00,443 --> 01:05:05,443
We can try.

955
01:05:05,740 --> 01:05:08,033
He wouldn't make more than a mouthful.

956
01:05:08,034 --> 01:05:10,994
Not when he's skinned and boned.

957
01:05:10,995 --> 01:05:12,579
Perhaps there's more...

958
01:05:12,580 --> 01:05:15,207
...burglar Hobbits around these parts.
Might be enough...

959
01:05:15,208 --> 01:05:17,459
...for a pie.

960
01:05:17,460 --> 01:05:19,628
- Grab him!
- He's too quick.

961
01:05:19,629 --> 01:05:23,131
Right. Come here, you little...

962
01:05:23,132 --> 01:05:24,633
Gotcha.

963
01:05:24,634 --> 01:05:27,093
Are there any more of you little fellas...

964
01:05:27,094 --> 01:05:30,263
- ...hiding where you shouldn't?
- No.

965
01:05:30,264 --> 01:05:31,806
He's lying.

966
01:05:31,807 --> 01:05:36,311
- No, I'm not!
- Hold his toes over the fire.

967
01:05:36,312 --> 01:05:39,481
Make him squeal!

968
01:05:42,443 --> 01:05:43,693
Drop him!

969
01:05:43,694 --> 01:05:45,862
You what?

970
01:05:45,863 --> 01:05:47,614
I said...

971
01:05:47,615 --> 01:05:48,865
...drop him.

972
01:06:11,430 --> 01:06:13,056
Get the sacks!

973
01:06:13,057 --> 01:06:16,393
Stick them in the sacks!

974
01:06:37,623 --> 01:06:42,623
Ow!

975
01:07:04,567 --> 01:07:05,483
Come on!

976
01:07:05,484 --> 01:07:07,110
Get up!

977
01:07:07,111 --> 01:07:10,030
- Bilbo!
- Don't!

978
01:07:10,031 --> 01:07:12,699
Lay down your arms...

979
01:07:12,700 --> 01:07:17,700
...or we'll rip his off.

980
01:07:29,175 --> 01:07:33,136
- Oh! That's hot, that's hot, that's hot!
- Don't bother cooking them.

981
01:07:33,137 --> 01:07:37,557
Let's just sit on them
and squash them into jelly.

982
01:07:37,558 --> 01:07:41,936
They should be sauteed and grilled
with a sprinkle of sage.

983
01:07:41,937 --> 01:07:43,646
Is this really necessary?

984
01:07:43,647 --> 01:07:45,607
That does sound quite nice.

985
01:07:45,608 --> 01:07:48,735
 - Untie me, mister.
- Eat someone your own size.

986
01:07:48,736 --> 01:07:50,820
Never mind the seasoning.

987
01:07:50,821 --> 01:07:53,573
We ain't got all night. Dawn ain't...

988
01:07:53,574 --> 01:07:56,284
...far away. Let's get a move on.

989
01:07:56,285 --> 01:08:01,285
I don't fancy being turned to stone.

990
01:08:01,415 --> 01:08:02,916
Wait!

991
01:08:02,917 --> 01:08:04,250
You are making...

992
01:08:04,251 --> 01:08:06,127
...a terrible mistake.

993
01:08:06,128 --> 01:08:07,670
You can't reason with them.

994
01:08:07,671 --> 01:08:09,130
- They're half-wits!
- Half-wits?

995
01:08:09,131 --> 01:08:11,174
What does that make us?

996
01:08:11,175 --> 01:08:13,134
I meant with...

997
01:08:13,135 --> 01:08:14,302
...the seasoning.

998
01:08:14,303 --> 01:08:17,138
What about the seasoning?

999
01:08:17,139 --> 01:08:18,681
Well, have you smelt them?

1000
01:08:18,682 --> 01:08:22,435
You're gonna need something stronger
than sage before you plate this lot up.

1001
01:08:22,436 --> 01:08:24,062
- Traitor!
 - What do you know...

1002
01:08:24,063 --> 01:08:26,106
...about cooking Dwarf?

1003
01:08:26,107 --> 01:08:27,440
Shut up.

1004
01:08:27,441 --> 01:08:32,028
Let the flurgaburburhobbit talk.

1005
01:08:32,029 --> 01:08:35,156
The secret to cooking Dwarf is...

1006
01:08:35,157 --> 01:08:38,451
- Yes? Come on. Tell us the secret.
- It's, uh...

1007
01:08:38,452 --> 01:08:42,997
Yes, I'm telling you. The secret is...

1008
01:08:42,998 --> 01:08:44,958
...to skin them first.

1009
01:08:44,959 --> 01:08:47,961
What? Skin us?

1010
01:08:47,962 --> 01:08:49,754
Tom, get me filleting knife.

1011
01:08:49,755 --> 01:08:51,589
I'll skin you, you little...!

1012
01:08:51,590 --> 01:08:53,591
I won't forget that. I won't forget it.

1013
01:08:53,592 --> 01:08:56,136
What a load of rubbish.

1014
01:08:56,137 --> 01:08:59,222
I've eaten plenty with their skins on.

1015
01:08:59,223 --> 01:09:00,348
Scarf them, I say...

1016
01:09:00,349 --> 01:09:02,225
...boots and all.

1017
01:09:02,226 --> 01:09:04,686
He's right.

1018
01:09:04,687 --> 01:09:09,687
Nothing wrong with a bit of raw Dwarf.

1019
01:09:09,984 --> 01:09:12,527
Nice and crunchy.

1020
01:09:12,528 --> 01:09:13,945
Oh, not that one.

1021
01:09:13,946 --> 01:09:15,280
He's infected.

1022
01:09:15,281 --> 01:09:16,197
Huh?

1023
01:09:16,198 --> 01:09:17,198
You what?

1024
01:09:17,199 --> 01:09:21,494
Yeah, he's got worms in his tubes.

1025
01:09:21,495 --> 01:09:22,495
Eww!

1026
01:09:22,496 --> 01:09:23,663
Aah!

1027
01:09:23,664 --> 01:09:25,415
In fact, they all have.

1028
01:09:25,416 --> 01:09:28,209
They're infested with parasites.
It's a terrible business.

1029
01:09:28,210 --> 01:09:30,128
I wouldn't risk it. I wouldn't.

1030
01:09:30,129 --> 01:09:31,045
Parasites?

1031
01:09:31,046 --> 01:09:33,131
Did he say "parasites"?

1032
01:09:33,132 --> 01:09:35,884
We don't have parasites.
You have parasites!

1033
01:09:35,885 --> 01:09:38,011
What are you talking about, laddie?

1034
01:09:41,307 --> 01:09:43,349
I've got parasites as big as my arm.

1035
01:09:43,350 --> 01:09:46,144
Mine are the biggest parasites.
I've got huge parasites.

1036
01:09:48,022 --> 01:09:49,689
- We're riddled.
 - Yes, I'm riddled.

1037
01:09:49,690 --> 01:09:51,107
Yes, we are, badly.

1038
01:09:51,108 --> 01:09:54,152
What would you have us do, then?

1039
01:09:54,153 --> 01:09:56,029
Let them all go?

1040
01:09:56,030 --> 01:09:57,697
- Well...
 - You think...

1041
01:09:57,698 --> 01:09:59,782
...I don't know what you're up to?

1042
01:09:59,783 --> 01:10:00,867
This little...

1043
01:10:00,868 --> 01:10:04,120
...ferret is taking us for fools.

1044
01:10:04,121 --> 01:10:05,121
Ferret?

1045
01:10:05,122 --> 01:10:06,080
Fools?

1046
01:10:06,081 --> 01:10:10,418
The dawn will take you all.

1047
01:10:10,419 --> 01:10:11,377
Who's that?

1048
01:10:11,378 --> 01:10:12,295
No idea.

1049
01:10:12,296 --> 01:10:16,758
Can we eat him too?

1050
01:10:39,490 --> 01:10:42,450
Get your foot out of my back.

1051
01:10:48,040 --> 01:10:51,334
Ah.

1052
01:10:51,335 --> 01:10:52,335
Where did you...

1053
01:10:52,336 --> 01:10:53,920
...go to, if I may ask?

1054
01:10:53,921 --> 01:10:55,922
To look ahead.

1055
01:10:55,923 --> 01:10:57,090
What brought you back?

1056
01:10:57,091 --> 01:10:59,759
Looking behind.

1057
01:10:59,760 --> 01:11:01,177
Nasty business.

1058
01:11:01,178 --> 01:11:02,929
Still, they're all in one piece.

1059
01:11:02,930 --> 01:11:05,765
No thanks to your burglar.

1060
01:11:05,766 --> 01:11:09,269
He had the nous to play for time.

1061
01:11:09,270 --> 01:11:13,731
None of the rest of you thought of that.

1062
01:11:13,732 --> 01:11:16,859
They must have come down
from the Ettenmoors.

1063
01:11:16,860 --> 01:11:19,862
Since when do Mountain Trolls
venture this far south?

1064
01:11:19,863 --> 01:11:22,657
Ooh. Not for an age.

1065
01:11:22,658 --> 01:11:27,658
Not since a darker power ruled these lands.

1066
01:11:31,959 --> 01:11:36,045
They could not have moved in daylight.

1067
01:11:36,046 --> 01:11:40,341
There must be a cave nearby.

1068
01:11:49,101 --> 01:11:51,603
Oh, what's that stench?

1069
01:11:51,604 --> 01:11:55,064
It's a Troll-hoard.

1070
01:11:55,065 --> 01:11:57,859
Be careful what you touch.

1071
01:12:10,122 --> 01:12:12,081
Seems a shame just to leave it...

1072
01:12:12,082 --> 01:12:15,293
...lying around.

1073
01:12:15,294 --> 01:12:17,420
- Anyone could take it.
- Agreed.

1074
01:12:17,421 --> 01:12:19,255
- Nori.
- Yeah?

1075
01:12:19,256 --> 01:12:24,256
Get a shovel.

1076
01:12:37,858 --> 01:12:42,858
These swords were not made by any Troll.

1077
01:12:45,908 --> 01:12:50,908
Nor were they made
by any smith among Men.

1078
01:12:54,875 --> 01:12:57,126
These were forged in Gondolin...

1079
01:12:57,127 --> 01:13:01,798
...by the High Elves of the First Age.
You could not...

1080
01:13:01,799 --> 01:13:06,799
...wish for a finer blade.

1081
01:13:17,314 --> 01:13:20,108
- Set it down.
- That's good.

1082
01:13:20,109 --> 01:13:25,109
All right, come on. Quick.

1083
01:13:30,077 --> 01:13:33,413
We're making a long-term deposit.

1084
01:13:33,414 --> 01:13:35,415
Let's get out of this foul place.

1085
01:13:35,416 --> 01:13:37,291
Come on, let's go.

1086
01:13:37,292 --> 01:13:42,292
Bofur, Gloin, Nori.

1087
01:13:58,731 --> 01:14:01,899
- Bilbo.
- Hmm?

1088
01:14:01,900 --> 01:14:03,151
Here.

1089
01:14:03,152 --> 01:14:08,152
This is about your size.

1090
01:14:11,326 --> 01:14:13,077
I can't take this.

1091
01:14:13,078 --> 01:14:15,288
The blade is of Elvish make...

1092
01:14:15,289 --> 01:14:16,998
...which means...

1093
01:14:16,999 --> 01:14:21,377
...it will glow blue
when Orcs or Goblins are nearby.

1094
01:14:21,378 --> 01:14:23,921
I have never used a sword in my life.

1095
01:14:23,922 --> 01:14:26,799
And I hope you never have to.

1096
01:14:26,800 --> 01:14:29,886
But if you do, remember this...

1097
01:14:29,887 --> 01:14:34,887
True courage is about knowing
not when to take a life...

1098
01:14:35,851 --> 01:14:40,851
...but when to spare one.

1099
01:14:43,442 --> 01:14:45,151
Something's coming!

1100
01:14:45,152 --> 01:14:46,068
Gandalf.

1101
01:14:46,069 --> 01:14:47,862
Stay together!

1102
01:14:47,863 --> 01:14:49,530
Hurry now!

1103
01:14:49,531 --> 01:14:54,531
Arm yourselves!

1104
01:15:09,259 --> 01:15:10,218
Thieves!

1105
01:15:10,219 --> 01:15:14,347
Fire! Murder!

1106
01:15:14,348 --> 01:15:16,724
Radagast.

1107
01:15:16,725 --> 01:15:18,851
It's Radagast the Brown.

1108
01:15:18,852 --> 01:15:22,730
Well...

1109
01:15:22,731 --> 01:15:24,607
What on earth are you doing here?

1110
01:15:24,608 --> 01:15:26,317
I was looking for you, Gandalf.

1111
01:15:26,318 --> 01:15:27,860
Something's wrong.

1112
01:15:27,861 --> 01:15:30,154
Something's terribly wrong.

1113
01:15:30,155 --> 01:15:33,825
Yes?

1114
01:15:33,826 --> 01:15:36,744
Oh.

1115
01:15:36,745 --> 01:15:38,913
Just give me a minute.

1116
01:15:38,914 --> 01:15:42,083
Oh. I had a thought and now I've lost it.

1117
01:15:42,084 --> 01:15:43,835
It was right there...

1118
01:15:43,836 --> 01:15:46,045
...on the tip of my tongue.

1119
01:15:46,046 --> 01:15:47,004
Oh.

1120
01:15:47,005 --> 01:15:49,423
It's not a thought at all.

1121
01:15:49,424 --> 01:15:52,218
It's a silly old...

1122
01:15:52,219 --> 01:15:57,219
...stick insect.

1123
01:15:58,100 --> 01:16:02,353
The Greenwood is sick, Gandalf.

1124
01:16:02,354 --> 01:16:04,730
A darkness has fallen over it.

1125
01:16:04,731 --> 01:16:07,108
Nothing grows anymore.

1126
01:16:07,109 --> 01:16:09,360
At least, nothing good.

1127
01:16:09,361 --> 01:16:12,196
The air is foul with decay.

1128
01:16:12,197 --> 01:16:14,156
But worse are the webs.

1129
01:16:14,157 --> 01:16:16,492
Webs? What do you mean?

1130
01:16:16,493 --> 01:16:18,786
Spiders, Gandalf.

1131
01:16:18,787 --> 01:16:20,371
Giant ones.

1132
01:16:20,372 --> 01:16:25,042
Some kind of spawn of Ungoliant,
or I am not a Wizard.

1133
01:16:25,043 --> 01:16:27,295
I followed their trail.

1134
01:16:27,296 --> 01:16:31,173
They came from Dol Guldur.

1135
01:16:31,174 --> 01:16:33,009
Huh?

1136
01:16:33,010 --> 01:16:35,219
Dol Guldur?

1137
01:16:35,220 --> 01:16:39,265
But the old fortress is abandoned.

1138
01:16:39,266 --> 01:16:42,435
No, Gandalf.

1139
01:16:42,436 --> 01:16:47,436
'Tis not.

1140
01:16:52,613 --> 01:16:55,615
<i>A dark power dwells in there...

1141
01:16:55,616 --> 01:16:57,742
<i>...such as I have never...

1142
01:16:57,743 --> 01:17:00,786
<i>...felt before.

1143
01:17:00,787 --> 01:17:05,787
<i>It is the shadow of an ancient horror.

1144
01:17:11,214 --> 01:17:15,051
<i>One that can summon the spirits...

1145
01:17:15,052 --> 01:17:20,052
<i>...of the dead.

1146
01:17:33,278 --> 01:17:35,905
<i>I saw him, Gandalf.

1147
01:17:35,906 --> 01:17:38,950
<i>From out of the darkness...

1148
01:17:38,951 --> 01:17:41,160
<i>...a Necromancer...

1149
01:17:41,161 --> 01:17:42,954
<i>...has come.

1150
01:17:42,955 --> 01:17:47,041
Radagast.

1151
01:17:50,629 --> 01:17:55,216
Quick! Quick, quick! Quick, quick!

1152
01:17:55,217 --> 01:18:00,217
Wait for me!

1153
01:18:10,607 --> 01:18:12,024
Sorry.

1154
01:18:12,025 --> 01:18:14,610
Try a little Old Toby.

1155
01:18:14,611 --> 01:18:19,611
It'll help settle your nerves.

1156
01:18:19,700 --> 01:18:21,283
And out.

1157
01:18:28,500 --> 01:18:29,542
Now...

1158
01:18:29,543 --> 01:18:34,543
...a Necromancer. Are you sure?

1159
01:18:46,601 --> 01:18:48,310
That is not...

1160
01:18:48,311 --> 01:18:53,311
...from the world of the living.

1161
01:18:58,280 --> 01:19:01,282
Was that a wolf?
Are there wolves out there?

1162
01:19:01,283 --> 01:19:04,326
Wolves? No, that is not a wolf.

1163
01:19:09,624 --> 01:19:14,624
Kili! Get your bow!

1164
01:19:18,383 --> 01:19:20,051
Warg scouts.

1165
01:19:20,052 --> 01:19:22,261
Which means an Orc pack is not far behind.

1166
01:19:22,262 --> 01:19:23,387
Orc pack?

1167
01:19:23,388 --> 01:19:24,972
Who did you tell about your quest...

1168
01:19:24,973 --> 01:19:26,640
...beyond your kin?

1169
01:19:26,641 --> 01:19:27,558
No one.

1170
01:19:27,559 --> 01:19:28,476
Who did you tell?

1171
01:19:28,477 --> 01:19:30,269
No one, I swear.

1172
01:19:30,270 --> 01:19:31,187
What in...

1173
01:19:31,188 --> 01:19:32,438
...Durin's name is going on?

1174
01:19:32,439 --> 01:19:35,274
You are being hunted.

1175
01:19:35,275 --> 01:19:36,734
We have to get out of here.

1176
01:19:36,735 --> 01:19:38,110
We can't. We have no ponies.

1177
01:19:39,112 --> 01:19:40,946
They bolted.

1178
01:19:40,947 --> 01:19:42,448
I'll draw them off.

1179
01:19:42,449 --> 01:19:44,408
These are Gundabad Wargs.

1180
01:19:44,409 --> 01:19:45,576
They will outrun you.

1181
01:19:45,577 --> 01:19:48,579
These are Rhosgobel rabbits.

1182
01:19:48,580 --> 01:19:52,124
I'd like to see them try.

1183
01:19:59,007 --> 01:20:00,508
<font color=#FF0000>Kogum!</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(There!)</font>

1184
01:20:00,509 --> 01:20:02,927
Come on! Come on!

1185
01:20:02,928 --> 01:20:05,513
Come and get me! Ha, ha!

1186
01:20:05,514 --> 01:20:07,348
<font color=#FF0000>Zidg!</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(Wizard!)</font>

1187
01:20:14,481 --> 01:20:19,481
Come on.

1188
01:20:44,010 --> 01:20:45,302
Stay together.

1189
01:20:45,303 --> 01:20:50,303
Move!

1190
01:20:57,566 --> 01:21:02,566
Ori, no! Get back.

1191
01:21:03,196 --> 01:21:07,783
All of you, come on. Quick!

1192
01:21:07,784 --> 01:21:12,784
Where are you leading us?

1193
01:22:06,009 --> 01:22:08,900
{\an8}<font color=#FF0000>Khozdayin harish huru nar!</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(The Dwarves, they travels towards East!)</font>

1194
01:22:11,000 --> 01:22:12,500
{\an8}<font color=#FF0000>Gur!</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(Quickly!)</font>

1195
01:22:18,271 --> 01:22:19,563
Move!

1196
01:22:19,564 --> 01:22:24,564
Run!

1197
01:22:37,707 --> 01:22:40,876
There they are!

1198
01:22:40,877 --> 01:22:42,127
This way!

1199
01:22:42,128 --> 01:22:47,128
Quickly!

1200
01:22:54,557 --> 01:22:56,976
There's more coming!

1201
01:22:56,977 --> 01:22:58,143
Kili!

1202
01:22:58,144 --> 01:23:01,000
Shoot them!

1203
01:23:04,025 --> 01:23:05,900
We're surrounded!

1204
01:23:09,948 --> 01:23:11,615
Where's Gandalf?

1205
01:23:11,616 --> 01:23:16,616
He's abandoned us.

1206
01:23:19,791 --> 01:23:24,791
Hold your ground!

1207
01:23:29,200 --> 01:23:31,000
<font color=#FF8000>Ithrik√Æ!</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(Steady!)</font>

1208
01:23:31,511 --> 01:23:33,679
This way, you fools!

1209
01:23:33,680 --> 01:23:35,000
Come on, move!

1210
01:23:37,183 --> 01:23:38,142
Quickly!

1211
01:23:38,143 --> 01:23:39,310
All of you!

1212
01:23:39,311 --> 01:23:41,478
Come on!

1213
01:23:41,479 --> 01:23:43,000
Go, go, go!

1214
01:23:53,241 --> 01:23:56,493
Eight, nine, 10.

1215
01:23:56,494 --> 01:23:57,453
Kili!

1216
01:23:57,454 --> 01:23:58,704
Run!

1217
01:24:38,620 --> 01:24:42,831
Elves.

1218
01:24:42,832 --> 01:24:44,083
I cannot see where the...

1219
01:24:44,084 --> 01:24:46,960
...pathway leads.
Do we follow it or no?

1220
01:24:46,961 --> 01:24:51,961
Follow it, of course.

1221
01:24:52,050 --> 01:24:57,050
I think that would be wise.

1222
01:25:17,367 --> 01:25:18,867
Gandalf.

1223
01:25:18,868 --> 01:25:20,577
Where are we?

1224
01:25:20,578 --> 01:25:21,703
You can feel it?

1225
01:25:21,704 --> 01:25:26,083
Yes. It feels like...

1226
01:25:26,084 --> 01:25:27,543
Well, like magic.

1227
01:25:27,544 --> 01:25:30,254
That's exactly what it is.

1228
01:25:30,255 --> 01:25:33,966
A very powerful magic.

1229
01:25:33,967 --> 01:25:38,967
There's light ahead.

1230
01:26:16,676 --> 01:26:20,679
The Valley of Imladris.

1231
01:26:20,680 --> 01:26:24,892
In the common tongue,
it's known by another name.

1232
01:26:24,893 --> 01:26:29,188
Rivendell.

1233
01:26:29,189 --> 01:26:34,189
Here lies the Last Homely House
East of the Sea.

1234
01:26:35,111 --> 01:26:38,447
This was your plan all along.

1235
01:26:38,448 --> 01:26:40,699
To seek refuge with our enemy.

1236
01:26:40,700 --> 01:26:44,203
You have no enemies here,
Thorin Oakenshield.

1237
01:26:44,204 --> 01:26:46,330
The only ill will to be found...

1238
01:26:46,331 --> 01:26:49,416
...in this valley
is that which you bring yourself.

1239
01:26:49,417 --> 01:26:53,754
You think the Elves will give our quest
their blessing?

1240
01:26:53,755 --> 01:26:55,380
They will try to stop us.

1241
01:26:55,381 --> 01:27:00,381
Of course they will. But we have questions
that need to be answered.

1242
01:27:02,889 --> 01:27:06,683
If we are to be successful,
this will need to be handled with tact.

1243
01:27:06,684 --> 01:27:08,227
And respect.

1244
01:27:08,228 --> 01:27:10,896
And no small degree of charm.

1245
01:27:10,897 --> 01:27:15,897
<i>Which is why you will leave
the talking to me.

1246
01:28:11,374 --> 01:28:13,917
Mithrandir.

1247
01:28:13,918 --> 01:28:14,960
Ah.

1248
01:28:14,961 --> 01:28:16,628
Lindir.

1249
01:28:16,629 --> 01:28:19,172
Stay sharp.

1250
01:28:19,173 --> 01:28:21,675
{\an8}<font color=#008000>Lastannem i athrannedh i Vruinen.
<font color=#FFFF00>(We heard that you had crossed the Loudwater.)</font>

1251
01:28:21,676 --> 01:28:23,760
I must speak with Lord Elrond.

1252
01:28:23,761 --> 01:28:26,179
My Lord Elrond is not here.

1253
01:28:26,180 --> 01:28:28,849
Not here?

1254
01:28:28,850 --> 01:28:30,309
Where is he?

1255
01:28:43,197 --> 01:28:44,740
<font color=#FF8000>Ifrid√Æ bek√¢r!</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(Ready weapons!)</font>

1256
01:28:44,741 --> 01:28:49,741
Close ranks!

1257
01:29:10,391 --> 01:29:11,683
Gandalf.

1258
01:29:11,684 --> 01:29:15,354
Lord Elrond.

1259
01:29:15,355 --> 01:29:18,857
{\an8}<font color=#008000>Mellonnen! Mo ev√≠nedh?
<font color=#FFFF00>(My friend! Where have you gone?)</font>

1260
01:29:18,858 --> 01:29:22,000
{\an8}<font color=#008000>Farannem 'lamhoth i udul o charad.
<font color=#FFFF00>(We've been hunting Orcs that came from the South.)</font>

1261
01:29:24,000 --> 01:29:27,500
{\an8}<font color=#008000>Dagannem rim na Iant Vedui.
<font color=#FFFF00>(We slew a number at the Last Bridge.)</font>

1262
01:29:30,536 --> 01:29:34,790
Strange for Orcs to come
so close to our borders.

1263
01:29:34,791 --> 01:29:38,960
Something or someone
has drawn them near.

1264
01:29:38,961 --> 01:29:43,961
Ah. That may have been us.

1265
01:29:46,260 --> 01:29:49,805
Welcome, Thorin, son of Thrain.

1266
01:29:49,806 --> 01:29:52,683
I do not believe we have met.

1267
01:29:52,684 --> 01:29:55,936
You have your grandfather's bearing.

1268
01:29:55,937 --> 01:29:57,688
I knew Thror when he ruled...

1269
01:29:57,689 --> 01:30:02,689
- ...Under the Mountain.
- Indeed? He made no mention of you.

1270
01:30:05,363 --> 01:30:08,300
<font color=#008000>Nartho i noer, toltho i viruvor.
<font color=#FFFF00>(Light the fires, fetch the miruvor.)</font>

1271
01:30:09,000 --> 01:30:12,900
<font color=#008000>Boe i annam vann a nethail vin.
<font color=#FFFF00>(We must give food to our guests.)</font>

1272
01:30:13,079 --> 01:30:15,539
What is he saying?

1273
01:30:15,540 --> 01:30:18,166
Does he offer us insult?

1274
01:30:18,167 --> 01:30:23,167
No, Master Gloin, he's offering you food.

1275
01:30:28,469 --> 01:30:29,761
Well...

1276
01:30:29,762 --> 01:30:33,014
...in that case, lead on.

1277
01:30:33,015 --> 01:30:34,391
Hey. Come on.

1278
01:30:34,392 --> 01:30:37,436
Try it. Just a mouthful.

1279
01:30:37,437 --> 01:30:40,230
I don't like green food.

1280
01:30:40,231 --> 01:30:41,398
Where's the meat?

1281
01:30:42,859 --> 01:30:45,318
Have they got any chips?

1282
01:30:45,319 --> 01:30:46,361
Kind of you...

1283
01:30:46,362 --> 01:30:47,988
...to invite us.

1284
01:30:47,989 --> 01:30:49,740
Not really dressed for dinner.

1285
01:30:49,741 --> 01:30:51,158
Well, you never are.

1286
01:31:10,553 --> 01:31:14,014
I can't say I fancy Elf maids myself, too thin.

1287
01:31:14,015 --> 01:31:15,807
They're all high cheekbones...

1288
01:31:15,808 --> 01:31:18,101
...and creamy skin.

1289
01:31:18,102 --> 01:31:19,686
Not enough facial hair for me.

1290
01:31:19,687 --> 01:31:24,649
Although that one there is not bad.

1291
01:31:24,650 --> 01:31:29,650
That's not an Elf maid.

1292
01:31:38,164 --> 01:31:43,164
That's funny.

1293
01:31:51,219 --> 01:31:55,514
This is Orcrist, the Goblin-cleaver.

1294
01:31:55,515 --> 01:31:57,307
A famous blade...

1295
01:31:57,308 --> 01:32:02,308
...forged by the High Elves
of the West, my kin.

1296
01:32:03,356 --> 01:32:05,440
May it serve you well.

1297
01:32:05,441 --> 01:32:06,483
And this...

1298
01:32:06,484 --> 01:32:09,486
...is Glamdring...

1299
01:32:09,487 --> 01:32:11,196
...the Foehammer. Sword...

1300
01:32:11,197 --> 01:32:13,532
...of the King of Gondolin.

1301
01:32:13,533 --> 01:32:16,243
These were made for the Goblin Wars
of the First Age.

1302
01:32:16,244 --> 01:32:17,536
I wouldn't bother, laddie.

1303
01:32:17,537 --> 01:32:21,206
Swords are named
for the great deeds they do in war.

1304
01:32:21,207 --> 01:32:23,959
What are you saying,
my sword hasn't seen battle?

1305
01:32:23,960 --> 01:32:27,879
I'm not actually sure it is a sword.

1306
01:32:27,880 --> 01:32:31,007
More of a letter opener, really.

1307
01:32:31,008 --> 01:32:32,676
- How did you come by these?
- We found them...

1308
01:32:32,677 --> 01:32:35,512
...in a Troll-hoard on the Great East Road...

1309
01:32:35,513 --> 01:32:36,680
...shortly before...

1310
01:32:36,681 --> 01:32:40,934
- ...we were ambushed by Orcs.
- And what were you doing...

1311
01:32:40,935 --> 01:32:44,271
...on the Great East Road?

1312
01:32:44,272 --> 01:32:49,272
Excuse me.

1313
01:32:53,114 --> 01:32:54,948
Thirteen Dwarves...

1314
01:32:54,949 --> 01:32:56,616
...and a Halfling. Hm.

1315
01:32:56,617 --> 01:32:59,828
Strange traveling companions, Gandalf.

1316
01:32:59,829 --> 01:33:02,581
These are the descendants
of the house of Durin.

1317
01:33:02,582 --> 01:33:04,791
They're noble, decent folk.

1318
01:33:04,792 --> 01:33:07,919
And they're surprisingly cultured.

1319
01:33:07,920 --> 01:33:08,920
They've got a deep love...

1320
01:33:08,921 --> 01:33:11,715
- ...of the arts.
- Change the tune, why don't you?

1321
01:33:11,716 --> 01:33:13,550
I feel like I'm at a funeral.

1322
01:33:13,551 --> 01:33:15,176
- Did somebody die?
- All right...

1323
01:33:15,177 --> 01:33:20,177
...lads. There's only one thing for it.

1324
01:33:20,808 --> 01:33:23,226
<i>There's

1325
01:33:23,227 --> 01:33:24,936
<i>An

1326
01:33:24,937 --> 01:33:27,272
<i>Inn, there's an inn
There's a merry old inn

1327
01:33:27,273 --> 01:33:29,190
<i>Beneath an old gray hill

1328
01:33:29,191 --> 01:33:32,652
<i>And there they brew a beer so brown
The Man in the Moon

1329
01:33:32,653 --> 01:33:34,154
<i>Himself came down
One night

1330
01:33:34,155 --> 01:33:35,280
<i>To drink his fill

1331
01:33:35,281 --> 01:33:36,656
<i>Oh

1332
01:33:36,657 --> 01:33:38,408
<i>The ostler has a tipsy cat

1333
01:33:38,409 --> 01:33:40,994
<i>That played a five-stringed fiddle

1334
01:33:40,995 --> 01:33:42,495
<i>And up and down he saws his bow

1335
01:33:42,496 --> 01:33:45,165
<i>Now squeaking high

1336
01:33:45,166 --> 01:33:47,792
<i>Now purring low

1337
01:33:49,503 --> 01:33:51,963
<i>Now sawing in the middle

1338
01:33:51,964 --> 01:33:53,214
<i>So

1339
01:33:53,215 --> 01:33:53,965
<i>The cat on the fiddle

1340
01:33:53,966 --> 01:33:56,760
<i>Played hey-diddle-diddle
A jig that'll wake the dead

1341
01:33:56,761 --> 01:33:58,637
<i>He squeaked and he sawed
And he quickened

1342
01:33:58,638 --> 01:33:59,512
<i>The tune
And the landlord

1343
01:33:59,513 --> 01:34:00,472
<i>Shook the Man

1344
01:34:00,473 --> 01:34:01,431
<i>In the Moon
"It's after

1345
01:34:01,432 --> 01:34:02,515
<i>Three!" he said!

1346
01:34:11,067 --> 01:34:13,276
Our business is no concern of Elves.

1347
01:34:13,277 --> 01:34:15,236
For goodness sake, Thorin...

1348
01:34:15,237 --> 01:34:17,113
...show him the map.
- It is the legacy...

1349
01:34:17,114 --> 01:34:18,615
...of my people.

1350
01:34:18,616 --> 01:34:22,369
It is mine to protect, as are its secrets.

1351
01:34:22,370 --> 01:34:25,080
Save me from the stubbornness
of Dwarves.

1352
01:34:25,081 --> 01:34:28,208
Your pride will be your downfall.

1353
01:34:28,209 --> 01:34:31,294
You stand in the presence
of one of the few in Middle-earth...

1354
01:34:31,295 --> 01:34:36,295
...who can read that map.
Show it to Lord Elrond.

1355
01:34:42,056 --> 01:34:47,056
Thorin, no.

1356
01:34:53,192 --> 01:34:56,236
Erebor.

1357
01:34:56,237 --> 01:34:58,196
What is your interest...

1358
01:34:58,197 --> 01:35:01,324
...in this map?

1359
01:35:01,325 --> 01:35:03,201
It's mainly academic.

1360
01:35:03,202 --> 01:35:04,160
As you know...

1361
01:35:04,161 --> 01:35:09,161
...this sort of artifact
sometimes contains hidden text.

1362
01:35:13,587 --> 01:35:18,587
You still read ancient Dwarvish,
do you not?

1363
01:35:22,096 --> 01:35:24,389
<font color=#008000>Ah, cirth ithil.</font>

1364
01:35:24,390 --> 01:35:27,017
Moon runes?

1365
01:35:27,018 --> 01:35:29,644
Of course.

1366
01:35:29,645 --> 01:35:31,604
An easy thing to miss.

1367
01:35:31,605 --> 01:35:33,398
Well, in this case, that is true.

1368
01:35:33,399 --> 01:35:36,067
Moon runes can only be read
by the light of a moon...

1369
01:35:36,068 --> 01:35:38,403
...of the same shape and season...

1370
01:35:38,404 --> 01:35:41,239
...as the day on which they were written.

1371
01:35:41,240 --> 01:35:46,240
Can you read them?

1372
01:35:47,621 --> 01:35:50,874
These runes were written
on a Midsummer's Eve...

1373
01:35:50,875 --> 01:35:55,754
...by the light of a crescent moon
nearly 200 years ago.

1374
01:35:55,755 --> 01:35:59,466
It would seem you were meant
to come to Rivendell.

1375
01:35:59,467 --> 01:36:00,925
Fate is with you...

1376
01:36:00,926 --> 01:36:02,886
...Thorin Oakenshield. The same moon...

1377
01:36:02,887 --> 01:36:07,887
...shines upon us tonight.

1378
01:36:24,283 --> 01:36:25,450
"Stand by the...

1379
01:36:25,451 --> 01:36:29,037
...gray stone when the thrush knocks...

1380
01:36:29,038 --> 01:36:34,038
...and the setting sun with
the last light of Durin's Day...

1381
01:36:34,043 --> 01:36:38,588
- ...will shine upon the keyhole."
- Durin's Day?

1382
01:36:38,589 --> 01:36:42,217
It is the start of the Dwarves' new year,
when the last moon of autumn...

1383
01:36:42,218 --> 01:36:45,261
...and the first sun of winter
appear in the sky together.

1384
01:36:45,262 --> 01:36:47,347
This is ill news.

1385
01:36:47,348 --> 01:36:50,058
Summer is passing.
Durin's Day will soon be upon us.

1386
01:36:50,059 --> 01:36:51,518
We still have time.

1387
01:36:51,519 --> 01:36:54,145
- Time? For what?
- To find the entrance.

1388
01:36:54,146 --> 01:36:58,108
We have to be standing in exactly
the right spot at exactly the right time.

1389
01:36:58,109 --> 01:37:02,070
Then, and only then,
can the door be opened.

1390
01:37:02,071 --> 01:37:02,987
So this is...

1391
01:37:02,988 --> 01:37:06,491
...your purpose, to enter the mountain?

1392
01:37:06,492 --> 01:37:08,034
What of it?

1393
01:37:08,035 --> 01:37:12,580
There are some who would not deem it wise.

1394
01:37:12,581 --> 01:37:15,166
What do you mean?

1395
01:37:15,167 --> 01:37:20,167
You are not the only guardian
to stand watch over Middle-earth.

1396
01:37:44,572 --> 01:37:48,000
{\an8}<font color=#FF0000>Khozdayin, Dorguz...</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(The Dwarves, Master...)</font>

1397
01:37:49,200 --> 01:37:51,000
{\an8}<font color=#FF0000>...zuranimid.</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(...we lost them.)</font>

1398
01:37:55,200 --> 01:37:59,000
{\an8}<font color=#FF0000>Shugi golgai gelnakhanishim...</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(The elves-filth surrounded us...)</font>

1399
01:37:59,128 --> 01:38:04,128
{\an8}<font color=#FF0000>Sha nargiz ob-hakhtil...</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(I don't want excuses...)</font>

1400
01:38:08,000 --> 01:38:12,900
{\an8}<font color=#FF0000>Nargiz khobdi... Rani Khozdil!</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(I want the head of the Dwarf King!)</font>

1401
01:38:13,000 --> 01:38:17,000
{\an8}<font color=#FF0000>Murganish dum. Turim hag shad.
<font color=#FFFF00>(They outnumbered us to the end. We could do nothing.)</font>

1402
01:38:17,500 --> 01:38:21,000
{\an8}<font color=#FF0000>Zorzor go-kairaz obguraniz.</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(I hardly escaped with my life.)</font>

1403
01:38:21,400 --> 01:38:34,900
{\an8}<font color=#FF0000>Ki go-kairag baganig... Ombar bunish!
<font color=#FFFF00>(If you had paid with your life, it would be better!)</font>

1404
01:38:46,700 --> 01:38:51,000
{\an8}<font color=#FF0000>Khozd-sharkun gud sh√¢ kilyash-zag.
<font color=#FFFF00>(The Dwarves will not hide themselves for long.)</font>

1405
01:38:53,000 --> 01:38:59,000
{\an8}<font color=#FF0000>Zidgar obod tung nash ru khobdud!
<font color=#FFFF00>(Inform about there is a price on their head!)</font>

1406
01:40:18,600 --> 01:40:19,684
Not with your...

1407
01:40:19,685 --> 01:40:21,686
...companions?

1408
01:40:21,687 --> 01:40:26,687
Uh, no, I shan't be missed.

1409
01:40:28,110 --> 01:40:33,072
The truth is that most of them
don't think I should be on this journey.

1410
01:40:33,073 --> 01:40:35,783
Indeed?

1411
01:40:35,784 --> 01:40:39,078
I've heard that Hobbits are very resilient.

1412
01:40:42,374 --> 01:40:44,000
Really?

1413
01:40:44,001 --> 01:40:49,001
Mm.

1414
01:40:49,590 --> 01:40:54,590
I've also heard they're fond
of the comforts of home.

1415
01:40:57,473 --> 01:41:00,433
I've heard that it's unwise
to seek the council of Elves.

1416
01:41:00,434 --> 01:41:05,434
That they will answer with yes and no.

1417
01:41:12,154 --> 01:41:14,947
You are very welcome to stay here,
if that...

1418
01:41:14,948 --> 01:41:19,948
...is your wish.

1419
01:41:21,288 --> 01:41:25,500
{\an8}<font color=#008000>Taenen bar-en-abed athar glaind, nevui penim miruvor.
<font color=#FFFF00>(The kitchen is under enormous strain, we are almost out of wine.)</font>

1420
01:41:26,000 --> 01:41:28,300
{\an8}<font color=#008000>Manann ingadh namen i-darthathar?
<font color=#FFFF00>(How long do you think they will be with us?)</font>

1421
01:41:28,545 --> 01:41:30,715
{\an8}<font color=#008000>Mennar √∫no.</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(They are not going anywhere.)</font>

1422
01:41:47,606 --> 01:41:50,817
No, you did the same thing.
It's not like you didn't do it.

1423
01:41:50,818 --> 01:41:55,818
Dori! Here, take that.

1424
01:41:59,118 --> 01:42:03,287
Bombur!

1425
01:42:18,053 --> 01:42:20,054
Of course I was going to tell you.
I was waiting...

1426
01:42:20,055 --> 01:42:25,055
...for this very chance. And really, I think
you can trust that I know what I am doing.

1427
01:42:25,102 --> 01:42:27,854
Do you? That dragon has slept...

1428
01:42:27,855 --> 01:42:29,647
...for 60 years.

1429
01:42:29,648 --> 01:42:31,899
What will happen if your plan should fail...

1430
01:42:31,900 --> 01:42:34,861
- ...if you wake that beast?
- What if we succeed?

1431
01:42:34,862 --> 01:42:37,196
If the Dwarves take back the mountain...

1432
01:42:37,197 --> 01:42:39,073
...our defenses in the east
will be strengthened.

1433
01:42:39,074 --> 01:42:41,659
It is a dangerous move, Gandalf.

1434
01:42:41,660 --> 01:42:43,703
It is also dangerous to do nothing.

1435
01:42:43,704 --> 01:42:48,207
Oh, come, the throne of Erebor
is Thorin's birthright. What is it you fear?

1436
01:42:48,208 --> 01:42:50,084
Have you forgotten?

1437
01:42:50,085 --> 01:42:53,880
A strain of madness
runs deep in that family.

1438
01:42:53,881 --> 01:42:56,799
His grandfather lost his mind.
His father succumbed to...

1439
01:42:56,800 --> 01:42:58,551
...the same sickness.

1440
01:42:58,552 --> 01:43:01,304
Can you swear Thorin Oakenshield...

1441
01:43:01,305 --> 01:43:05,516
...will not also fall?

1442
01:43:05,517 --> 01:43:10,021
Gandalf, these decisions
do not rest with us alone. It is not...

1443
01:43:10,022 --> 01:43:14,650
...up to you or me to redraw
the map of Middle-earth.

1444
01:43:14,651 --> 01:43:18,696
With or without our help, these Dwarves
will march on the mountain.

1445
01:43:18,697 --> 01:43:21,782
They're determined to reclaim
their homeland.

1446
01:43:21,783 --> 01:43:26,783
I do not believe Thorin Oakenshield
feels that he is answerable to anyone.

1447
01:43:27,122 --> 01:43:28,998
Nor, for that matter, am I.

1448
01:43:28,999 --> 01:43:33,999
It is not me you must answer to.

1449
01:43:44,223 --> 01:43:46,807
Lady Galadriel.

1450
01:43:46,808 --> 01:43:48,600
Mithrandir.

1451
01:43:50,300 --> 01:43:54,857
{\an8}<font color=#008000>Gwenwin √Æn √∫nodui</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(Countless years has passed.)</font>

1452
01:43:54,858 --> 01:44:02,900
{\an8}<font color=#008000>Nae nin gwistant infanneth, mal √∫-eichia i Ch√≠ril Lorien.
<font color=#FFFF00>(Alas, age has changed me, but [it] does not change the Lady of Lorien.)</font>

1453
01:44:07,955 --> 01:44:11,332
I had no idea Lord Elrond had sent for you.

1454
01:44:11,333 --> 01:44:13,292
He didn't.

1455
01:44:13,293 --> 01:44:18,293
I did.

1456
01:44:20,425 --> 01:44:23,219
Ah.

1457
01:44:23,220 --> 01:44:25,137
Saruman.

1458
01:44:25,138 --> 01:44:29,809
You've been busy of late, my friend.

1459
01:44:29,810 --> 01:44:32,353
Tell me, Gandalf...

1460
01:44:32,354 --> 01:44:36,065
...did you think these plans
and schemes of yours...

1461
01:44:36,066 --> 01:44:38,150
...would go unnoticed?

1462
01:44:38,151 --> 01:44:40,820
Unnoticed?

1463
01:44:40,821 --> 01:44:42,405
No.

1464
01:44:42,406 --> 01:44:44,949
I'm simply doing what I feel to be right.

1465
01:44:44,950 --> 01:44:48,953
The dragon has long been on your mind.

1466
01:44:48,954 --> 01:44:51,163
That is true, my lady.

1467
01:44:51,164 --> 01:44:53,708
Smaug owes allegiance to no one.

1468
01:44:53,709 --> 01:44:56,711
But if he should side with the enemy...

1469
01:44:56,712 --> 01:44:59,797
...a dragon could be used
to terrible effect.

1470
01:44:59,798 --> 01:45:02,049
What enemy?

1471
01:45:02,050 --> 01:45:05,094
Gandalf, the enemy is defeated.

1472
01:45:05,095 --> 01:45:10,095
Sauron is vanquished.
He can never regain his full strength.

1473
01:45:11,893 --> 01:45:15,646
Does it not worry you
that the last of the Dwarf rings...

1474
01:45:15,647 --> 01:45:17,732
...should simply vanish...

1475
01:45:17,733 --> 01:45:19,984
...along with its bearer?

1476
01:45:19,985 --> 01:45:23,946
Of the seven Dwarf rings,
four were consumed by dragons...

1477
01:45:23,947 --> 01:45:27,408
...two were taken by Sauron
before he fell in Mordor.

1478
01:45:27,409 --> 01:45:32,409
The fate of the last Dwarf ring
remains unknown.

1479
01:45:34,374 --> 01:45:37,335
The ring that was worn by Thrain.

1480
01:45:37,336 --> 01:45:39,545
Without the ruling Ring of Power...

1481
01:45:39,546 --> 01:45:44,383
...the seven are of no value to the enemy.

1482
01:45:44,384 --> 01:45:45,301
To control...

1483
01:45:45,302 --> 01:45:46,677
...the other rings...

1484
01:45:46,678 --> 01:45:50,598
...he needs the One.

1485
01:45:50,599 --> 01:45:53,392
And that ring was lost long, long ago.

1486
01:45:53,393 --> 01:45:54,602
It was swept out...

1487
01:45:54,603 --> 01:45:57,313
...to sea by the waters of the Anduin.

1488
01:45:57,314 --> 01:46:02,314
Gandalf, for 400 years
we have lived in peace...

1489
01:46:02,653 --> 01:46:04,403
...a hard-won...

1490
01:46:04,404 --> 01:46:05,905
...watchful peace.

1491
01:46:05,906 --> 01:46:09,992
Are we? Are we at peace?

1492
01:46:09,993 --> 01:46:14,993
Trolls have come down from the mountains.
They are raiding villages, destroying farms.

1493
01:46:15,165 --> 01:46:17,625
Orcs have attacked us on the road.

1494
01:46:17,626 --> 01:46:19,627
Hardly a prelude to war.

1495
01:46:19,628 --> 01:46:22,046
Always you must meddle...

1496
01:46:22,047 --> 01:46:24,215
...looking for trouble where none exists.

1497
01:46:24,216 --> 01:46:27,468
Let him speak.

1498
01:46:27,469 --> 01:46:32,469
There is something at work
beyond the evil of Smaug.

1499
01:46:32,641 --> 01:46:35,851
Something far more powerful.

1500
01:46:35,852 --> 01:46:40,852
We can remain blind to it, but it will not
be ignoring us, that I can promise you.

1501
01:46:41,441 --> 01:46:44,443
A sickness lies over the Greenwood.

1502
01:46:44,444 --> 01:46:47,446
The woodsmen who live there now
call it Mirkwood.

1503
01:46:47,447 --> 01:46:51,117
And they say...

1504
01:46:51,118 --> 01:46:52,034
Well?

1505
01:46:52,035 --> 01:46:54,078
Don't stop now.

1506
01:46:54,079 --> 01:46:56,580
Tell us what the woodsmen say.

1507
01:46:56,581 --> 01:46:59,083
They speak of a Necromancer...

1508
01:46:59,084 --> 01:47:00,459
...living in Dol Guldur.

1509
01:47:00,460 --> 01:47:03,671
A sorcerer who can summon the dead.

1510
01:47:03,672 --> 01:47:05,256
That's absurd.

1511
01:47:05,257 --> 01:47:08,259
No such power exists in this world.

1512
01:47:08,260 --> 01:47:12,638
This Necromancer is nothing more
than a mortal man.

1513
01:47:12,639 --> 01:47:15,349
A conjurer dabbling in black magic.

1514
01:47:15,350 --> 01:47:17,101
And so I thought too.

1515
01:47:17,102 --> 01:47:20,813
- But Radagast has seen...
- Radagast?

1516
01:47:20,814 --> 01:47:24,316
Do not speak to me
of Radagast the Brown.

1517
01:47:24,317 --> 01:47:26,318
He's a foolish fellow.

1518
01:47:26,319 --> 01:47:30,698
Well, he's odd, I grant you.
He lives a solitary life.

1519
01:47:30,699 --> 01:47:33,159
It's not that. It's his excessive...

1520
01:47:33,160 --> 01:47:35,578
...consumption of mushrooms.

1521
01:47:35,579 --> 01:47:37,204
They've addled his brain...

1522
01:47:37,205 --> 01:47:40,040
...and yellowed his teeth.

1523
01:47:40,041 --> 01:47:41,667
I've warned him.

1524
01:47:41,668 --> 01:47:45,087
It is unbefitting one of the Istari
to be wandering the woods...

1525
01:47:45,088 --> 01:47:48,883
<i>You carry something.

1526
01:47:48,884 --> 01:47:52,052
<i>It came to you from Radagast.

1527
01:47:52,053 --> 01:47:55,681
<i>He found it in Dol Guldur.

1528
01:47:55,682 --> 01:47:58,559
Yes.

1529
01:47:58,560 --> 01:48:02,146
Show me.

1530
01:48:02,147 --> 01:48:03,522
...listen to me.

1531
01:48:03,523 --> 01:48:07,526
I would think I was talking to myself
for all the attention that he paid.

1532
01:48:07,527 --> 01:48:10,404
By all means...

1533
01:48:10,405 --> 01:48:13,657
What is that?

1534
01:48:13,658 --> 01:48:18,658
A relic of Mordor.

1535
01:48:26,838 --> 01:48:29,006
A Morgul Blade.

1536
01:48:29,007 --> 01:48:32,343
Made for the Witchking of Angmar.

1537
01:48:32,344 --> 01:48:37,344
And buried with him.

1538
01:48:37,599 --> 01:48:39,850
When Angmar fell...

1539
01:48:39,851 --> 01:48:42,645
...the Men of the North took his body...

1540
01:48:42,646 --> 01:48:46,857
...and all that he possessed and sealed it
within the High Fells of Rhudaur.

1541
01:48:46,858 --> 01:48:50,569
Deep within the rock they buried him...

1542
01:48:50,570 --> 01:48:53,948
...in a tomb so dark...

1543
01:48:53,949 --> 01:48:55,741
...it would never come to light.

1544
01:48:55,742 --> 01:48:58,828
This is not possible.

1545
01:48:58,829 --> 01:49:01,789
A powerful spell lies upon those tombs.

1546
01:49:01,790 --> 01:49:03,833
They cannot be opened.

1547
01:49:03,834 --> 01:49:08,834
What proof do we have this weapon
came from Angmar's grave?

1548
01:49:09,297 --> 01:49:10,548
I have none.

1549
01:49:10,549 --> 01:49:13,384
Because there is none.

1550
01:49:13,385 --> 01:49:15,970
Let us examine what we know.

1551
01:49:15,971 --> 01:49:18,389
A single Orc pack...

1552
01:49:18,390 --> 01:49:21,350
...has dared to cross the Bruinen.

1553
01:49:21,351 --> 01:49:24,728
A dagger from a bygone age
has been found.

1554
01:49:24,729 --> 01:49:29,729
And a human sorcerer who calls himself
"The Necromancer"...

1555
01:49:30,318 --> 01:49:35,030
...has taken up residence
in a ruined fortress.

1556
01:49:35,031 --> 01:49:39,201
It's not so very much after all.

1557
01:49:39,202 --> 01:49:42,538
The question of this Dwarvish company,
however...

1558
01:49:42,539 --> 01:49:44,415
...troubles me deeply.

1559
01:49:44,416 --> 01:49:46,292
I'm not convinced, Gandalf.

1560
01:49:46,293 --> 01:49:50,170
I do not feel I can condone such a quest.

1561
01:49:50,171 --> 01:49:54,550
If they'd come to me, I might have
spared them this disappointment.

1562
01:49:54,551 --> 01:49:57,845
I do not pretend to understand your reason
for raising their hopes.

1563
01:49:57,846 --> 01:50:02,099
<i>They are leaving.

1564
01:50:02,100 --> 01:50:05,603
Yes.

1565
01:50:05,604 --> 01:50:07,646
You knew.

1566
01:50:10,984 --> 01:50:13,193
No, I'm afraid there is...

1567
01:50:13,194 --> 01:50:17,281
...nothing else for it.

1568
01:50:17,282 --> 01:50:19,199
My Lord Elrond.

1569
01:50:19,200 --> 01:50:24,200
The Dwarves, they're gone.

1570
01:50:27,459 --> 01:50:29,585
Be on your guard.

1571
01:50:29,586 --> 01:50:32,463
We're about to step over
the Edge of the Wild.

1572
01:50:32,464 --> 01:50:34,965
Balin, you know these paths. Lead on.

1573
01:50:34,966 --> 01:50:39,966
Aye.

1574
01:50:42,098 --> 01:50:44,141
Master Baggins...

1575
01:50:44,142 --> 01:50:49,142
...I suggest you keep up.

1576
01:51:00,033 --> 01:51:01,867
You will follow them.

1577
01:51:01,868 --> 01:51:03,202
Yes.

1578
01:51:03,203 --> 01:51:06,497
You are right to help Thorin Oakenshield.

1579
01:51:06,498 --> 01:51:09,917
But I fear this quest has set in motion...

1580
01:51:09,918 --> 01:51:13,629
...forces we do not yet understand.

1581
01:51:13,630 --> 01:51:17,716
The riddle of the Morgul Blade
must be answered.

1582
01:51:17,717 --> 01:51:21,428
Something moves in the shadows unseen,
hidden from our sight.

1583
01:51:21,429 --> 01:51:23,639
It will not show itself.

1584
01:51:23,640 --> 01:51:25,599
Not yet.

1585
01:51:25,600 --> 01:51:28,602
But every day it grows in strength.

1586
01:51:28,603 --> 01:51:33,603
You must be careful.

1587
01:51:35,026 --> 01:51:38,445
Mithrandir?

1588
01:51:38,446 --> 01:51:42,449
Why the Halfling?

1589
01:51:42,450 --> 01:51:46,996
I do not know.

1590
01:51:46,997 --> 01:51:51,000
Saruman believes
that it is only great power...

1591
01:51:51,001 --> 01:51:54,336
...that can hold evil in check.

1592
01:51:54,337 --> 01:51:57,965
But that is not what I have found.

1593
01:51:57,966 --> 01:52:01,885
I have found it is the small things...

1594
01:52:01,886 --> 01:52:04,430
...everyday deeds of ordinary folk...

1595
01:52:04,431 --> 01:52:08,100
...that keeps the darkness at bay.

1596
01:52:08,101 --> 01:52:13,101
Simple acts of kindness and love.

1597
01:52:13,481 --> 01:52:18,481
Why Bilbo Baggins?

1598
01:52:18,570 --> 01:52:23,198
Perhaps it is because I'm afraid...

1599
01:52:23,199 --> 01:52:28,199
...and he gives me courage.

1600
01:52:30,415 --> 01:52:35,415
Do not be afraid, Mithrandir.

1601
01:52:35,545 --> 01:52:40,545
You are not alone.

1602
01:52:40,842 --> 01:52:45,842
{\an8}<font color=#008000>Ae boe i le eliathon, im tulithon.
<font color=#FFFF00>(If it will be necessary to help you, I will come.)</font>

1603
01:54:17,188 --> 01:54:22,188
Hey! Hold on!

1604
01:54:26,114 --> 01:54:27,197
Aah!

1605
01:54:27,198 --> 01:54:28,490
Bilbo!

1606
01:54:30,827 --> 01:54:31,994
We must find...

1607
01:54:31,995 --> 01:54:34,037
...shelter!

1608
01:54:34,038 --> 01:54:39,038
Look out!

1609
01:54:41,838 --> 01:54:44,006
Look out, brother!

1610
01:54:44,007 --> 01:54:48,927
Hold on!

1611
01:54:48,928 --> 01:54:51,054
This is no thunderstorm.

1612
01:54:51,055 --> 01:54:54,391
It's a thunder-battle!

1613
01:54:54,392 --> 01:54:59,392
Look!

1614
01:55:00,440 --> 01:55:02,649
Well, bless me.

1615
01:55:02,650 --> 01:55:04,610
The legends are true.

1616
01:55:04,611 --> 01:55:09,611
Giants! Stone-Giants!

1617
01:55:15,663 --> 01:55:18,582
Take cover, you fool!

1618
01:55:18,583 --> 01:55:23,583
Hold on!

1619
01:55:28,593 --> 01:55:29,843
What's happening?

1620
01:55:29,844 --> 01:55:34,844
Grab my hand!

1621
01:55:54,953 --> 01:55:56,161
Go, go, go!

1622
01:55:56,162 --> 01:55:57,079
Run! Get off!

1623
01:55:57,080 --> 01:56:02,080
Get off!

1624
01:56:02,252 --> 01:56:07,252
- Run!
- Hold on!

1625
01:56:09,842 --> 01:56:14,842
Look out!

1626
01:56:31,698 --> 01:56:33,490
Jump!

1627
01:56:33,491 --> 01:56:38,491
Come on!

1628
01:56:38,663 --> 01:56:43,663
Hold on!

1629
01:56:48,172 --> 01:56:50,549
No!

1630
01:56:50,550 --> 01:56:55,550
No!

1631
01:57:00,810 --> 01:57:01,727
No!

1632
01:57:01,728 --> 01:57:06,728
Kili!

1633
01:57:09,193 --> 01:57:13,155
It's all right! They're alive!

1634
01:57:13,156 --> 01:57:14,448
Where's Bilbo?

1635
01:57:14,449 --> 01:57:15,699
Where's the Hobbit?

1636
01:57:17,035 --> 01:57:21,288
There!

1637
01:57:21,289 --> 01:57:23,540
Get him!

1638
01:57:23,541 --> 01:57:24,791
Aah!

1639
01:57:24,792 --> 01:57:25,709
Grab my hand!

1640
01:57:25,710 --> 01:57:28,420
Bilbo!

1641
01:57:28,421 --> 01:57:29,713
Ori, be careful!

1642
01:57:29,714 --> 01:57:31,089
Take it!

1643
01:57:31,090 --> 01:57:32,507
I've got you, lad.

1644
01:57:32,508 --> 01:57:37,508
Grab on! Grab on!

1645
01:57:43,728 --> 01:57:45,437
Come on.

1646
01:57:45,438 --> 01:57:46,730
Get him.

1647
01:57:46,731 --> 01:57:51,568
Come on, lad. Up you get.

1648
01:57:51,569 --> 01:57:54,488
I thought we'd lost our burglar.

1649
01:57:54,489 --> 01:57:57,866
He's been lost ever since he left home.

1650
01:57:57,867 --> 01:57:59,951
He should never have come.

1651
01:57:59,952 --> 01:58:03,747
He has no place amongst us.

1652
01:58:03,748 --> 01:58:08,748
Dwalin!

1653
01:58:11,464 --> 01:58:12,756
It looks safe enough.

1654
01:58:12,757 --> 01:58:14,466
Search to the back.

1655
01:58:14,467 --> 01:58:19,467
Caves in the mountain
are seldom unoccupied.

1656
01:58:20,765 --> 01:58:24,601
There's nothing here.

1657
01:58:24,602 --> 01:58:26,895
Right, then. Let's get a fire started.

1658
01:58:26,896 --> 01:58:29,981
No. No fires. Not in this place.

1659
01:58:29,982 --> 01:58:31,858
Get some sleep.

1660
01:58:31,859 --> 01:58:34,528
We start at first light.

1661
01:58:34,529 --> 01:58:38,407
We were to wait in the mountains
until Gandalf joined us.

1662
01:58:38,408 --> 01:58:39,950
That was the plan.

1663
01:58:39,951 --> 01:58:41,535
Plans change.

1664
01:58:41,536 --> 01:58:45,747
Bofur, take the first watch.

1665
01:58:52,338 --> 01:58:54,000
{\an8}<font color=#FF0000>Nuzdun gin nash.</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>(The scent is fresh.)</font>

1666
01:58:55,200 --> 01:59:00,000
{\an8}<font color=#FF0000>Khozdaikhun... Ord kirg gir hir haranish.
<font color=#FFFF00>(The dwarfdogs... They try [to] cross through [the] mountain pass.)</font>

1667
01:59:59,030 --> 01:59:59,946
Where do you think...

1668
01:59:59,947 --> 02:00:04,242
...You're going?

1669
02:00:04,243 --> 02:00:06,703
Back to Rivendell.

1670
02:00:06,704 --> 02:00:09,206
No, no, you can't turn back now, eh?

1671
02:00:09,207 --> 02:00:10,707
You're part of the company.

1672
02:00:10,708 --> 02:00:12,334
You're one of us.

1673
02:00:12,335 --> 02:00:15,462
I'm not, though, am I?

1674
02:00:15,463 --> 02:00:18,965
Thorin said I should never have come
and he was right.

1675
02:00:18,966 --> 02:00:20,008
I'm not a Took...

1676
02:00:20,009 --> 02:00:24,346
...I'm a Baggins.
I don't know what I was thinking.

1677
02:00:24,347 --> 02:00:26,264
I should never have run out my door.

1678
02:00:26,265 --> 02:00:28,683
You're homesick. I understand.

1679
02:00:28,684 --> 02:00:31,353
No, you don't. You don't understand.
None of you do.

1680
02:00:31,354 --> 02:00:34,231
You're Dwarves.
You're used to this life.

1681
02:00:34,232 --> 02:00:35,690
To living on the road...

1682
02:00:35,691 --> 02:00:40,691
...never settling in one place,
not belonging anywhere!

1683
02:00:42,114 --> 02:00:43,823
Oh, I am sorry. I didn't...

1684
02:00:49,330 --> 02:00:54,330
No, you're right.

1685
02:00:54,335 --> 02:00:59,335
We don't belong anywhere.

1686
02:01:04,554 --> 02:01:09,554
I wish you all the luck in the world.

1687
02:01:10,059 --> 02:01:15,059
I really do.

1688
02:01:15,898 --> 02:01:19,526
What's that?

1689
02:01:19,527 --> 02:01:24,527
Hmm?

1690
02:01:39,755 --> 02:01:41,047
Wake up!

1691
02:01:41,048 --> 02:01:42,090
Wake up!

1692
02:01:42,091 --> 02:01:43,341
Whoa!

1693
02:02:05,740 --> 02:02:10,619
Look out! Look out!

1694
02:02:10,620 --> 02:02:11,536
Get away!

1695
02:02:16,334 --> 02:02:18,001
Filthy scum!

1696
02:02:18,002 --> 02:02:23,002
Get back!

1697
02:02:23,966 --> 02:02:28,966
You'll pay for this!

1698
02:02:32,224 --> 02:02:35,060
Got you.

1699
02:02:35,061 --> 02:02:38,813
All right, all right.

1700
02:02:38,814 --> 02:02:43,814
Get off! Get your hands off me!
Get off me!

1701
02:02:47,198 --> 02:02:52,198
Get off me!

1702
02:04:29,508 --> 02:04:34,012
I feel a song coming on.

1703
02:04:36,307 --> 02:04:38,933
<i>Clap, snap
The black crack

1704
02:04:38,934 --> 02:04:41,603
<i>Grip, grab
Pinch and nab

1705
02:04:41,604 --> 02:04:43,480
<i>Batter and beat

1706
02:04:43,481 --> 02:04:46,232
<i>Make 'em stammer and

1707
02:04:46,233 --> 02:04:48,985
<i>Squeak

1708
02:04:48,986 --> 02:04:53,072
<i>Pound, pound
Far

1709
02:04:53,073 --> 02:04:58,073
<i>Underground

1710
02:04:59,955 --> 02:05:02,957
<i>Down, down, down in Goblin-town

1711
02:05:02,958 --> 02:05:05,043
<i>Down, down, down in Goblin-town

1712
02:05:05,044 --> 02:05:08,379
<i>With a swish and a smack
And a whip and a crack

1713
02:05:08,380 --> 02:05:11,341
<i>Everybody talks
When they're on my rack

1714
02:05:11,342 --> 02:05:14,886
<i>Pound, pound
Far underground

1715
02:05:14,887 --> 02:05:17,889
<i>Down, down, down to Goblin-town

1716
02:05:17,890 --> 02:05:20,767
<i>Down, down, down to Goblin-town

1717
02:05:20,768 --> 02:05:23,645
<i>Hammer and tongs
Get out your knockers and gongs

1718
02:05:23,646 --> 02:05:28,646
<i>You won't last long
On the end of my prong

1719
02:05:29,568 --> 02:05:31,444
<i>Clash, crash

1720
02:05:31,445 --> 02:05:32,946
<i>Crush and smash

1721
02:05:32,947 --> 02:05:35,490
<i>Bang, break
Shiver and shake

1722
02:05:35,491 --> 02:05:40,203
<i>You can yammer and yelp
But there ain't no help

1723
02:05:40,204 --> 02:05:45,204
<i>Pound, pound
Far underground

1724
02:05:45,709 --> 02:05:49,254
<i>Down, down, down in Goblin

1725
02:05:49,255 --> 02:05:54,255
<i>Town

1726
02:05:56,887 --> 02:06:00,223

Yeah!

1727
02:06:08,607 --> 02:06:10,692
Catchy, isn't it?

1728
02:06:10,693 --> 02:06:14,529
It's one of my own compositions.

1729
02:06:14,530 --> 02:06:16,155
That's not a song.

1730
02:06:16,156 --> 02:06:18,074
It's an abomination!

1731
02:06:18,075 --> 02:06:19,284
Abomination.

1732
02:06:19,285 --> 02:06:21,995
Mutations. Deviations.

1733
02:06:21,996 --> 02:06:26,996
That's all you're gonna find down here.

1734
02:06:28,794 --> 02:06:33,794
Who would be so bold
as to come armed into my kingdom?

1735
02:06:34,425 --> 02:06:35,592
Spies?

1736
02:06:35,593 --> 02:06:36,759
Thieves?

1737
02:06:36,760 --> 02:06:38,094
Assassins?

1738
02:06:38,095 --> 02:06:39,971
Dwarves, Your Malevolence.

1739
02:06:39,972 --> 02:06:41,890
Dwarves?

1740
02:06:41,891 --> 02:06:43,808
We found them on the Front Porch.

1741
02:06:43,809 --> 02:06:48,313
Well, don't just stand there. Search them.

1742
02:06:48,314 --> 02:06:49,689
Every crack.

1743
02:06:49,690 --> 02:06:54,690
Every crevice.

1744
02:06:57,573 --> 02:06:58,740
It is my belief...

1745
02:06:58,741 --> 02:07:01,284
...your great protuberance, that they...

1746
02:07:01,285 --> 02:07:03,244
...are in league with Elves!

1747
02:07:03,245 --> 02:07:07,290
"Made in Rivendell." Ah.

1748
02:07:07,291 --> 02:07:12,291
Second Age. Couldn't give it away.

1749
02:07:13,422 --> 02:07:15,882
Just a couple of keepsakes.

1750
02:07:15,883 --> 02:07:19,510
What are you doing in these parts?

1751
02:07:19,511 --> 02:07:23,389
Uh, don't worry, lads. I'll handle this.

1752
02:07:23,390 --> 02:07:24,933
What's...? What's that?

1753
02:07:24,934 --> 02:07:29,934
No tricks. I want the truth, warts and all.

1754
02:07:29,939 --> 02:07:32,774
You're going to have to speak up.

1755
02:07:32,775 --> 02:07:35,443
Your boys flattened my trumpet.

1756
02:07:35,444 --> 02:07:39,405
I'll flatten more than your trumpet!

1757
02:07:39,406 --> 02:07:43,952
If it's more information you want,
I'm the one you should speak to.

1758
02:07:43,953 --> 02:07:47,705
Mm-hm.

1759
02:07:47,706 --> 02:07:51,709
We were on the road.
Well, it's not so much a road as a path.

1760
02:07:51,710 --> 02:07:54,504
It's not even that, come to think of it.
More like a track.

1761
02:07:54,505 --> 02:07:58,174
Anyway, the point is, we were on this road,
like a path, like a track.

1762
02:07:58,175 --> 02:08:01,803
And then we weren't, which is a problem,
because we were...

1763
02:08:01,804 --> 02:08:03,137
- ...supposed to be in Dunland...
- Shut up.

1764
02:08:03,138 --> 02:08:04,555
